{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-88ee18bf8326b9b3", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\tAudio-Native Speech Recognition with a Frozen Discrete-Diffusion Language Model \n2\t\n3\tTitle: \n4\tContent selection saved. Describe the issue below: \n5\tDescription: \n6\t\n7\tarXiv is now an independent nonprofit! \n8\tLearn more \n9\t× \n10\t\n11\tLicense: arXiv.org perpetual non-exclusive license \n12\tarXiv:2607.13013v1 [cs.AI] 14 Jul 2026 \n13\t\n14\tAudio-Native Speech Recognition with a Frozen Discrete-Diffusion Language Model \n15\tHarsha Vardhan Khurdula 1 \n16\t\n17\tAbhinav Kumar Singh 2 \n18\t\n19\tYoeven D Khemlani 2 \n20\t\n21\tVineet Agarwal 2 \n22\t\n23\tInterfaze AI San Francisco, CA, USA {harsha, abhinav, yoeven, vineet}@interfaze.ai \n24\t\n25\tAbstract \n26\tAutomatic speech recognition is dominated by autoregressive decoders that emit one token at a time. We ask whether a discrete diffusion language model can transcribe speech instead, refining a whole transcript in parallel over a small number of denoising steps. We train an audio-native interface for DiffusionGemma, a 26B mixture-of-experts model that generates text by uniform, random-token discrete diffusion rather than the absorbing-mask scheme common to recent diffusion language models. A frozen Whisper encoder supplies acoustic features, a lightweight projector maps them into the model embedding space, and low-rank adapters let the frozen backbone attend to the new modality. \n27\tAbout 42M parameters are trained, which is 0.16 percent of the backbone. We find that the natural training objectives fail to ground the audio, because their gradient reaches the projector only through attention that has already dismissed it. A connectionist temporal classification loss applied through the frozen output head breaks this deadlock. The resulting model reaches 6.6 percent word error rate on LibriSpeech test-clean, transcribes in roughly eight parallel steps regardless of utterance length, and uses a single adapter trained on six languages, which we evaluate here on English, Hindi, and Mandarin. \n28\t\n29\tAudio-Native Speech Recognition with a Frozen Discrete-Diffusion Language Model \n30\t\n31\tHarsha Vardhan Khurdula 1 \n32\t\n33\tAbhinav Kumar Singh 2 \n34\t\n35\tYoeven D Khemlani 2 \n36\t\n37\tVineet Agarwal 2 \n38\t\n39\tInterfaze AI \n40\t\n41\tSan Francisco, CA, USA \n42\t\n43\t{harsha, abhinav, yoeven, vineet}@interfaze.ai \n44\t\n45\t1 \n46\tIntroduction \n47\tSpeech recognition has been decoded the same way for a long time. An encoder reads the audio, and an attention decoder spells the transcript one token at a time, feeding each token back to itself to produce the next (Chan et al., 2016 \n48\t; Radford et al., 2023 \n49\t) \n50\t. The encoders have grown very strong, but the decoder is serial by construction, so a thirty second clip costs a few hundred sequential forward passes no matter how much hardware is available. Diffusion language models decode differently, starting from a canvas of noise and refining the whole sequence in parallel over a small number of denoising steps; they now reach quality competitive with autoregressive models of similar size (Nie et al., 2025 \n51\t) \n52\t. The natural question is whether speech can be transcribed the same way, so that the cost of recognition is set by the number of denoising steps and not by the length of the transcript. \n53\t\n54\tTwo systems have shown that diffusion can transcribe. TransFusion denoised character sequences with multinomial diffusion (Baas et al., 2022 \n55\t) \n56\t, and Whisfusion trained a masked-diffusion decoder on top of frozen Whisper features (Kwon et al., 2025 \n57\t) \n58\t. Both train a decoder specifically for the task, and both are English only. We ask a different question: can an existing, general-purpose diffusion language model be taught to hear, so that recognition runs through its own decoder with no new decoder trained at all? \n59\t\n60\tWe take DiffusionGemma, an open-weight 26B mixture-of-experts model that generates text by discrete diffusion (does not have audio support), and give it a native audio input. We keep the backbone frozen. We add a frozen Whisper encoder as an acoustic feature extractor (Radford et al., 2023 \n61\t) \n62\t, a small trainable projector that maps those features into the model embedding space, and low-rank adapters (Hu et al., 2022 \n63\t) \n64\tso the frozen model can learn to attend to the new modality. The projector-into-language-model recipe follows the connectors that gave sight and hearing to text-only models (Liu et al., 2023 \n65\t; Chu et al., 2023 \n66\t; Rubenstein et al., 2023 \n67\t) \n68\t, applied here for the first time to a diffusion decoder. Only about 42M parameters train, which is 0.16 percent of the backbone. The result reaches 6.6 percent word error rate on LibriSpeech test-clean, converges in about eight parallel steps regardless of utterance length, and uses a single adapter trained on six languages. \n69\t\n70\tThe challenge lied in grounding, a frozen language model has never seen a spectrogram, so its embedding space has no notion of formants or phonemes, and the two obvious training objectives both route their signal through cross-attention. If attention has already decided the audio is noise, no gradient reaches the projector to make it useful, and the projector stays noise, which in turn gives attention no reason to change. We break this deadlock with a connectionist temporal classification loss applied directly through the frozen output head, which forces the audio embeddings to be linearly predictive of the transcript without asking attention to trust them first. \n71\t\n72\tOur contributions are the following. \n73\t• \n74\tAn audio-native pathway for a frozen discrete-diffusion language model, trained only through a projector and low-rank adapters, with no decoder trained from scratch. \n75\t\n76\t• \n77\tA diagnosis of the grounding failure and a direct-supervision fix that breaks the projector and attention deadlock in a few hundred steps. \n78\t\n79\t• \n80\tAn empirical study of the accuracy and speed of diffusion decoding for speech, including a step count sweep that shows recognition cost decoupled from transcript length. \n81\t\n82\t• \n83\tA single adapter trained on six languages (English, German, French, Spanish, Hindi, Mandarin) and evaluated here on English, Hindi, and Mandarin, together with an analysis of where it trails autoregressive Whisper and why. \n84\t\n85\t2 \n86\tBackground \n87\t2.1 \n88\tThe diffusion backbone \n89\tDiffusionGemma is a 26B mixture-of-experts model with 128 experts, top-8 routing, and roughly 4B active parameters per token. It has 30 transformer layers, a hidden size of 2816, and a vocabulary of 262144. It generates text by discrete diffusion rather than autoregression. \n90\t\n91\tMost recent diffusion language models use an absorbing state, where corruption replaces tokens with a special <mask> \n92\tsymbol and generation fills masks in (Austin et al., 2021 \n93\t; Lou et al., 2024 \n94\t; Nie et al., 2025 \n95\t) \n96\t. DiffusionGemma instead uses uniform, random-token diffusion. It starts from a fixed-length canvas, up to 256 slots, filled with random tokens drawn from the vocabulary. At each denoising step the model reads the whole canvas at once, keeps the low-entropy predictions it is confident about, and renoises the remaining positions back to fresh random tokens. After a few steps the noise anneals into text (Figure 1 \n97\t\n98\t). Training mirrors this process. A clean sequence is corrupted by replacing a fraction γ \n99\t\\gamma \n100\t\n101\tof positions with uniform random tokens, and the model is trained to recover the originals at the corrupted positions. We formalize the process in Section 3.4 \n102\t\n103\t. \n104\t\n105\tFigure 1: \n106\tUniform discrete diffusion in DiffusionGemma. Generation starts from a canvas of random vocabulary tokens and, over a few steps, keeps the confident predictions and renoises the rest until the canvas anneals into text. There is no absorbing mask state. \n107\t\n108\t2.2 \n109\tEncoder-decoder structure \n110\tArchitecturally the model is an encoder-decoder with tied transformer weights. The encoder reads the prompt causally into a read-only key-value cache. The decoder refines the canvas with bidirectional self-attention while cross-attending to that cache. Multimodal inputs are injected by scattering projected features into placeholder token positions of the encoder input embeddings. The existing vision path uses an image token identifier for this. Out of the box the model accepts text, images, and video, and produces text. It does not accept audio and providing that modality is one of our key contributions in our work. \n111\t\n112\t2.3 \n113\tConnecting an encoder to a language model \n114\tA frozen language model can be given a new input modality by training a small connector that maps features from a modality encoder into the model embedding space, while the backbone stays fixed or is only lightly adapted. This recipe added vision to text-only models through a projector over a vision encoder (Liu et al., 2023 \n115\t) \n116\t, and audio to language models through speech encoders and adapters (Chu et al., 2023 \n117\t; Rubenstein et al., 2023 \n118\t) \n119\t, usually on top of open model families such as Gemma (Gemma Team, 2024 \n120\t) \n121\t. Our audio pathway follows the same pattern. What is new is the decoder it feeds. Every connector we are aware of feeds an autoregressive model, whereas here the connector conditions a diffusion decoder that produces the transcript in parallel, which changes both how the model must be grounded and how it decodes. \n122\t\n123\t3 \n124\tMethod \n125\tFigure 2: \n126\tThe audio-native pathway. A frozen Whisper encoder produces acoustic features, a trainable projector maps them to T \n127\t= \n128\t188 \n129\t\n130\tT{=}188 \n131\t\n132\taudio tokens in the model embedding space, and these are scattered into the placeholder positions of the encoder prompt. The frozen DiffusionGemma encoder reads the prompt into a key-value cache, and the decoder denoises the transcript canvas in parallel while attending to that cache. Three losses train the projector and the low-rank adapters. The diffusion loss and the autoregressive auxiliary loss route through attention, and the connectionist temporal classification loss is applied directly through the frozen output head. \n133\t\n134\t3.1 \n135\tNotation and setup \n136\tLet 𝒱 \n137\t\\mathcal{V} \n138\t\n139\tbe the vocabulary with V \n140\t= \n141\t| \n142\t𝒱 \n143\t| \n144\t\n145\t= \n146\t262 \n147\t\n148\t, \n149\t144 \n150\t\n151\tV=|\\mathcal{V}|=262{,}144 \n152\t\n153\t. A transcript is a token sequence 𝐲 \n154\t= \n155\t( \n156\ty \n157\t1 \n158\t\n159\t, \n160\t… \n161\t, \n162\ty \n163\tM \n164\t\n165\t) \n166\t\n167\t\\mathbf{y}=(y_{1},\\dots,y_{M}) \n168\t\n169\t. We write it onto a fixed canvas of length L \n170\tL \n171\t\n172\t(we use L \n173\t= \n174\t256 \n175\t\n176\tL{=}256 \n177\t\n178\tin training and L \n179\t= \n180\t192 \n181\t\n182\tL{=}192 \n183\t\n184\tat inference) as the clean target 𝐱 \n185\t0 \n186\t\n187\t= \n188\t( \n189\t𝐲 \n190\t, \n191\teos \n192\t, \n193\tpad \n194\t, \n195\t… \n196\t) \n197\t\n198\t∈ \n199\t𝒱 \n200\tL \n201\t\n202\t\\mathbf{x}_{0}=(\\mathbf{y},\\textsc{eos},\\textsc{pad},\\dots)\\in\\mathcal{V}^{L} \n203\t\n204\t. The audio is a log-mel spectrogram 𝐦 \n205\t∈ \n206\tℝ \n207\t80 \n208\t× \n209\t3000 \n210\t\n211\t\\mathbf{m}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{80\\times 3000} \n212\t\n213\t, since Whisper pads or trims to thirty seconds. We keep the DiffusionGemma backbone and the Whisper encoder frozen and train only a projector 𝒫 \n214\tϕ \n215\t\n216\t\\mathcal{P}_{\\phi} \n217\t\n218\tand low-rank adapters θ \n219\t\\theta \n220\t\n221\t. We write σ \n222\tτ \n223\t\n224\t​ \n225\t( \n226\tz \n227\t) \n228\t\n229\t= \n230\tτ \n231\t​ \n232\ttanh \n233\t⁡ \n234\t( \n235\tz \n236\t/ \n237\tτ \n238\t\n239\t) \n240\t\n241\t\\sigma_{\\tau}(z)=\\tau\\tanh(z/\\tau) \n242\t\n243\tfor the final logit softcap with τ \n244\t= \n245\t30 \n246\t\n247\t\\tau{=}30 \n248\t\n249\t, and W \n250\tU \n251\t\n252\t∈ \n253\tℝ \n254\tV \n255\t× \n256\td \n257\t\n258\tW_{U}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{V\\times d} \n259\t\n260\tfor the frozen tied output head, with model width d \n261\t= \n262\t2816 \n263\t\n264\td{=}2816 \n265\t\n266\t. The overall architecture is shown in Figure 2 \n267\t\n268\t. \n269\t\n270\t3.2 \n271\tAudio pathway \n272\tIn our first attempt, we skipped the acoustic encoder entirely. Some unified Gemma models project raw waveforms straight into the embedding space, so we fed the model short audio frames and let the backbone infer the acoustics to test this approach. And it failed completely, as a frozen language model that has never seen audio cannot build an acoustic front end from gradient signal alone, and a shallow projector cannot do feature extraction on its own. Word error rate plateaued near 94 percent while the model produced fluent text unrelated to the audio. \n273\t\n274\tThe working design uses a frozen Whisper-small encoder (Radford et al., 2023 \n275\t) \n276\tas a feature extractor, not as a decoder. It carries the acoustic modeling that self-supervised representations (Baevski et al., 2020 \n277\t) \n278\tand convolution-augmented transformers (Gulati et al., 2020 \n279\t) \n280\testablished, which is the map from sound to linguistic features a frozen text model cannot learn on its own. The encoder produces 𝐚 \n281\t∈ \n282\tℝ \n283\tF \n284\t× \n285\td \n286\tw \n287\t\n288\t\\mathbf{a}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{F\\times d_{w}} \n289\t\n290\twith F \n291\t= \n292\t1500 \n293\t\n294\tF{=}1500 \n295\t\n296\tframes and d \n297\tw \n298\t\n299\t= \n300\t768 \n301\t\n302\td_{w}{=}768 \n303\t\n304\t. The projector maps these to audio tokens 𝐮 \n305\t∈ \n306\tℝ \n307\tT \n308\t× \n309\td \n310\t\n311\t\\mathbf{u}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{T\\times d} \n312\t\n313\t, \n314\t\n315\t𝐡 \n316\t( \n317\t0 \n318\t) \n319\t\n320\t\\displaystyle\\mathbf{h}^{(0)} \n321\t\n322\t= \n323\tGELU \n324\t​ \n325\t( \n326\t𝐚 \n327\t​ \n328\tW \n329\tin \n330\t\n331\t) \n332\t\n333\t, \n334\t\n335\t\\displaystyle=\\mathrm{GELU}(\\mathbf{a}\\,W_{\\text{in}}), \n336\t\n337\t(1) \n338\t\n339\t𝐡 \n340\t( \n341\tl \n342\t) \n343\t\n344\t\\displaystyle\\mathbf{h}^{(l)} \n345\t\n346\t= \n347\tGELU \n348\t\n349\t​ \n350\t( \n351\tConv1d \n352\t( \n353\tl \n354\t) \n355\t\n356\t​ \n357\t( \n358\t𝐡 \n359\t( \n360\tl \n361\t− \n362\t1 \n363\t\n364\t) \n365\t\n366\t) \n367\t\n368\t) \n369\t\n370\t, \n371\tl \n372\t= \n373\t1 \n374\t, \n375\t2 \n376\t, \n377\t3 \n378\t\n379\t, \n380\t\n381\t\\displaystyle=\\mathrm{GELU}\\!\\big(\\mathrm{Conv1d}^{(l)}(\\mathbf{h}^{(l-1)})\\big),\\quad l=1,2,3, \n382\t\n383\t(2) \n384\t\n385\t𝐮 \n386\t\\displaystyle\\mathbf{u} \n387\t\n388\t= \n389\tLN \n390\t\n391\t​ \n392\t( \n393\t𝐡 \n394\t( \n395\t3 \n396\t) \n397\t\n398\t​ \n399\tW \n400\tout \n401\t\n402\t) \n403\t\n404\t, \n405\t\n406\t\\displaystyle=\\mathrm{LN}\\!\\big(\\mathbf{h}^{(3)}\\,W_{\\text{out}}\\big), \n407\t\n408\t(3) \n409\t\n410\twith W \n411\tin \n412\t\n413\t∈ \n414\tℝ \n415\td \n416\tw \n417\t\n418\t× \n419\td \n420\th \n421\t\n422\tW_{\\text{in}}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{d_{w}\\times d_{h}} \n423\t\n424\t, W \n425\tout \n426\t\n427\t∈ \n428\tℝ \n429\td \n430\th \n431\t\n432\t× \n433\td \n434\t\n435\tW_{\\text{out}}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{d_{h}\\times d} \n436\t\n437\t, hidden width d \n438\th \n439\t\n440\t= \n441\t1280 \n442\t\n443\td_{h}{=}1280 \n444\t\n445\t, and convolutions of kernel 3, stride 2, and padding 1. Each convolution maps a length n \n446\tn \n447\t\n448\tto ⌊ \n449\t( \n450\tn \n451\t− \n452\t1 \n453\t\n454\t) \n455\t\n456\t/ \n457\t2 \n458\t\n459\t⌋ \n460\t\n461\t+ \n462\t1 \n463\t\n464\t\\lfloor(n-1)/2\\rfloor+1 \n465\t\n466\t, so 1500 \n467\t→ \n468\t750 \n469\t→ \n470\t375 \n471\t→ \n472\t188 \n473\t\n474\t1500\\to 750\\to 375\\to 188 \n475\t\n476\tand T \n477\t= \n478\t188 \n479\t\n480\tT{=}188 \n481\t\n482\t, about 6.25 tokens per second. The projector, together with the adapters introduced below, is the only trained part of the model. \n483\t\n484\t3.3 \n485\tConditioning the diffusion decoder on audio \n486\tWe build a fixed-length prompt \n487\t\n488\t[BOS] \n489\t​ \n490\tinstr \n491\t​ \n492\t[BOA] \n493\t​ \n494\t( \n495\t<audio> \n496\t) \n497\t\n498\t× \n499\tT \n500\t\n501\t​ \n502\t[EOA] \n503\t\n504\t, \n505\t\n506\t\\texttt{[BOS]}\\ \\text{instr}\\ \\texttt{[BOA]}\\ \\big(\\texttt{<audio>}\\big)^{\\!\\times T}\\ \\texttt{[EOA]}, \n507\t\n508\twith audio placeholder positions 𝒜 \n509\t\\mathcal{A} \n510\t\n511\t, | \n512\t𝒜 \n513\t| \n514\t\n515\t= \n516\tT \n517\t\n518\t|\\mathcal{A}|{=}T \n519\t\n520\t. We embed the prompt and overwrite the placeholders with the projected audio tokens, \n521\t\n522\t𝐄 \n523\tj \n524\t\n525\t= \n526\t{ \n527\t𝐮 \n528\tρ \n529\t​ \n530\t( \n531\tj \n532\t) \n533\t\n534\tj \n535\t∈ \n536\t𝒜 \n537\t\n538\t, \n539\t\n540\tEmb \n541\t​ \n542\t( \n543\tc \n544\tj \n545\t\n546\t) \n547\t\n548\totherwise, \n549\t\n550\t\\mathbf{E}_{j}=\\begin{cases}\\mathbf{u}_{\\rho(j)}&j\\in\\mathcal{A},\\\\[2.0pt]\n551\t\\mathrm{Emb}(c_{j})&\\text{otherwise,}\\end{cases} \n552\t\n553\t(4) \n554\t\n555\twhere ρ \n556\t\\rho \n557\t\n558\tindexes projector rows, reusing the scatter mechanism the vision path uses. The frozen encoder, with adapters θ \n559\t\\theta \n560\t\n561\t, reads this into a key-value cache 𝐊 \n562\t= \n563\tEnc \n564\tθ \n565\t\n566\t​ \n567\t( \n568\t𝐄 \n569\t) \n570\t\n571\t\\mathbf{K}=\\mathrm{Enc}_{\\theta}(\\mathbf{E}) \n572\t\n573\t, and the decoder cross-attends to 𝐊 \n574\t\\mathbf{K} \n575\t\n576\twhile denoising, as in Eq. 6 \n577\t\n578\t. The prompt length is constant because T \n579\tT \n580\t\n581\tis fixed. For clips shorter than thirty seconds we zero the attention mask on the silence-pad audio positions so the encoder ignores them. The canvas holds the transcript, an end-of-sequence marker, and padding, and is the decoder target 𝐱 \n582\t0 \n583\t\n584\t\\mathbf{x}_{0} \n585\t\n586\t. \n587\t\n588\t3.4 \n589\tUniform discrete diffusion \n590\tWith the audio in the cache, we can state the generation process. Unlike the absorbing-state schemes used by most diffusion language models (Austin et al., 2021 \n591\t; Lou et al., 2024 \n592\t; Nie et al., 2025 \n593\t) \n594\t, DiffusionGemma corrupts toward uniform random tokens rather than a mask. A single scalar γ \n595\t∈ \n596\t[ \n597\t0 \n598\t, \n599\t1 \n600\t] \n601\t\n602\t\\gamma\\in[0,1] \n603\t\n604\tsets the corruption level and plays the role a timestep plays in continuous diffusion. Corruption acts independently at each position, \n605\t\n606\tq \n607\t​ \n608\t( \n609\tx \n610\tγ \n611\ti \n612\t\n613\t= \n614\tk \n615\t∣ \n616\tx \n617\t0 \n618\ti \n619\t\n620\t; \n621\tγ \n622\t\n623\t) \n624\t\n625\t= \n626\t( \n627\t1 \n628\t− \n629\tγ \n630\t\n631\t) \n632\t\n633\t​ \n634\t1 \n635\t​ \n636\t[ \n637\tk \n638\t= \n639\tx \n640\t0 \n641\ti \n642\t\n643\t] \n644\t\n645\t+ \n646\tγ \n647\tV \n648\t\n649\t, \n650\t\n651\tq(x_{\\gamma}^{i}=k\\mid x_{0}^{i};\\gamma)=(1-\\gamma)\\,\\mathbf{1}[k=x_{0}^{i}]+\\frac{\\gamma}{V}, \n652\t\n653\t(5) \n654\t\n655\twhich is the cumulative uniform D3PM kernel Q \n656\t¯ \n657\t\n658\tγ \n659\t\n660\t= \n661\t( \n662\t1 \n663\t− \n664\tγ \n665\t\n666\t) \n667\t\n668\t​ \n669\tI \n670\t\n671\t+ \n672\tγ \n673\tV \n674\t\n675\t​ \n676\t𝟏𝟏 \n677\t⊤ \n678\t\n679\t\\bar{Q}_{\\gamma}=(1-\\gamma)\\,I+\\tfrac{\\gamma}{V}\\mathbf{1}\\mathbf{1}^{\\!\\top} \n680\t\n681\t(Austin et al., 2021 \n682\t) \n683\t. Equivalently, draw b \n684\ti \n685\t\n686\t∼ \n687\tBernoulli \n688\t​ \n689\t( \n690\tγ \n691\t) \n692\t\n693\tb_{i}\\sim\\mathrm{Bernoulli}(\\gamma) \n694\t\n695\tand r \n696\ti \n697\t\n698\t∼ \n699\tUnif \n700\t​ \n701\t( \n702\t𝒱 \n703\t) \n704\t\n705\tr_{i}\\sim\\mathrm{Unif}(\\mathcal{V}) \n706\t\n707\tand set x \n708\tγ \n709\ti \n710\t\n711\t= \n712\t( \n713\t1 \n714\t− \n715\tb \n716\ti \n717\t\n718\t) \n719\t\n720\t​ \n721\tx \n722\t0 \n723\ti \n724\t\n725\t+ \n726\tb \n727\ti \n728\t\n729\t​ \n730\tr \n731\ti \n732\t\n733\tx_{\\gamma}^{i}=(1-b_{i})\\,x_{0}^{i}+b_{i}\\,r_{i} \n734\t\n735\t. There is no special mask symbol, so a corrupted position holds a real, random vocabulary token. \n736\t\n737\tThe model is trained in the 𝐱 \n738\t0 \n739\t\n740\t\\mathbf{x}_{0} \n741\t\n742\tparameterization. Given the corrupted canvas and the audio conditioning 𝐜 \n743\t\\mathbf{c} \n744\t\n745\tcarried by the cache 𝐊 \n746\t\\mathbf{K} \n747\t\n748\t, it predicts the clean token at each position, \n749\t\n750\tp \n751\tθ \n752\t, \n753\tϕ \n754\t\n755\t​ \n756\t( \n757\tx \n758\t0 \n759\ti \n760\t\n761\t∣ \n762\t𝐱 \n763\tγ \n764\t\n765\t, \n766\t𝐜 \n767\t\n768\t) \n769\t\n770\t\\displaystyle p_{\\theta,\\phi}(x_{0}^{i}\\mid\\mathbf{x}_{\\gamma},\\mathbf{c}) \n771\t\n772\t= \n773\tsoftmax \n774\t\n775\t​ \n776\t( \n777\tσ \n778\tτ \n779\t\n780\t​ \n781\t( \n782\tW \n783\tU \n784\t\n785\t​ \n786\t𝐡 \n787\ti \n788\t\n789\t) \n790\t\n791\t) \n792\t\n793\t, \n794\t\n795\t\\displaystyle=\\mathrm{softmax}\\!\\big(\\sigma_{\\tau}(W_{U}\\,\\mathbf{h}_{i})\\big), \n796\t\n797\t(6) \n798\t\n799\t𝐡 \n800\t\\displaystyle\\mathbf{h} \n801\t\n802\t= \n803\tDec \n804\tθ \n805\t\n806\t​ \n807\t( \n808\t𝐱 \n809\tγ \n810\t\n811\t, \n812\t𝐊 \n813\t) \n814\t\n815\t. \n816\t\n817\t\\displaystyle=\\mathrm{Dec}_{\\theta}(\\mathbf{x}_{\\gamma},\\mathbf{K}). \n818\t\n819\t3.5 \n820\tTraining objectives \n821\tThree losses share one projector and one set of adapters. \n822\t\n823\tDiffusion loss. \n824\tThis is the model’s own objective, the reweighted 𝐱 \n825\t0 \n826\t\n827\t\\mathbf{x}_{0} \n828\t\n829\t-prediction surrogate of the discrete-diffusion variational bound (Austin et al., 2021 \n830\t; Ho et al., 2020 \n831\t) \n832\t. Let 𝒞 \n833\t\\mathcal{C} \n834\t\n835\tbe the corrupted, non-pad positions. Taking the expectation over γ \n836\t∼ \n837\tUnif \n838\t​ \n839\t( \n840\t0 \n841\t, \n842\t1 \n843\t) \n844\t\n845\t\\gamma\\sim\\mathrm{Unif}(0,1) \n846\t\n847\t, the data, and the corruption, \n848\t\n849\tℒ \n850\tdiff \n851\t\n852\t= \n853\t𝔼 \n854\t\n855\t​ \n856\t[ \n857\tw \n858\t​ \n859\t( \n860\tγ \n861\t) \n862\t\n863\t| \n864\t𝒞 \n865\t| \n866\t\n867\t​ \n868\t∑ \n869\ti \n870\t∈ \n871\t𝒞 \n872\t\n873\t− \n874\tlog \n875\t⁡ \n876\tp \n877\tθ \n878\t, \n879\tϕ \n880\t\n881\t​ \n882\t( \n883\tx \n884\t0 \n885\ti \n886\t\n887\t∣ \n888\t𝐱 \n889\tγ \n890\t\n891\t, \n892\t𝐜 \n893\t\n894\t) \n895\t\n896\t] \n897\t\n898\t, \n899\t\n900\t\\mathcal{L}_{\\text{diff}}=\\mathbb{E}\\!\\left[\\frac{w(\\gamma)}{|\\mathcal{C}|}\\sum_{i\\in\\mathcal{C}}-\\log p_{\\theta,\\phi}(x_{0}^{i}\\mid\\mathbf{x}_{\\gamma},\\mathbf{c})\\right], \n901\t\n902\t(7) \n903\t\n904\twith an optional importance weight w \n905\t​ \n906\t( \n907\tγ \n908\t) \n909\t\n910\t∈ \n911\t{ \n912\t1 \n913\t, \n914\t1 \n915\t/ \n916\tγ \n917\t\n918\t} \n919\t\n920\tw(\\gamma)\\in\\{1,\\,1/\\gamma\\} \n921\t\n922\t. The loss is applied only at corrupted positions. Because the objective is bidirectional and the frozen text prior explains much of the visible clean context, the gradient asking the model to use audio is diluted (Section 3.6 \n923\t\n924\t). We therefore force γ \n925\t= \n926\t1 \n927\t\n928\t\\gamma{=}1 \n929\t\n930\ton a fraction of batches, where the audio is the only source of information. \n931\t\n932\tAutoregressive auxiliary loss. \n933\tThe encoder is causal, so we can teacher-force the transcript through it and read a standard next-token loss, \n934\t\n935\tℒ \n936\tar \n937\t\n938\t= \n939\t𝔼 \n940\t​ \n941\t[ \n942\t1 \n943\tM \n944\t\n945\t​ \n946\t∑ \n947\ti \n948\t= \n949\t1 \n950\t\n951\tM \n952\t\n953\t− \n954\tlog \n955\t⁡ \n956\tsoftmax \n957\t\n958\t​ \n959\t( \n960\tσ \n961\tτ \n962\t\n963\t​ \n964\t( \n965\tW \n966\tU \n967\t\n968\t​ \n969\t𝐠 \n970\ti \n971\t\n972\t) \n973\t\n974\t) \n975\t\n976\ty \n977\ti \n978\t\n979\t] \n980\t\n981\t, \n982\t\n983\t\\mathcal{L}_{\\text{ar}}=\\mathbb{E}\\Big[\\frac{1}{M}\\sum_{i=1}^{M}-\\log\\,\\mathrm{softmax}\\!\\big(\\sigma_{\\tau}(W_{U}\\mathbf{g}_{i})\\big)_{y_{i}}\\Big], \n984\t\n985\t(8) \n986\t\n987\twhere 𝐠 \n988\ti \n989\t\n990\t\\mathbf{g}_{i} \n991\t\n992\tis the encoder state that predicts y \n993\ti \n994\t\n995\ty_{i} \n996\t\n997\tfrom 𝐲 \n998\t\n999\t< \n1000\ti \n1001\t\n1002\t\\mathbf{y}_{<i} \n1003\t\n1004\tand the audio. Because the encoder shares weights with the diffusion decoder and reads the same audio tokens, this dense per-token gradient transfers to parallel denoising. \n1005\t\n1006\tCTC loss. \n1007\tWe decode the projector rows directly through the frozen output head, with no softcap, and align them to the transcript with connectionist temporal classification (Graves et al., 2006 \n1008\t) \n1009\t. With per-frame distributions 𝐪 \n1010\tt \n1011\t\n1012\t= \n1013\tsoftmax \n1014\t​ \n1015\t( \n1016\tW \n1017\tU \n1018\t\n1019\t​ \n1020\t𝐮 \n1021\tt \n1022\t\n1023\t) \n1024\t\n1025\t\\mathbf{q}_{t}=\\mathrm{softmax}(W_{U}\\mathbf{u}_{t}) \n1026\t\n1027\tand the blank symbol at index 0, \n1028\t\n1029\tℒ \n1030\tctc \n1031\t\n1032\t= \n1033\t− \n1034\tlog \n1035\t\n1036\t​ \n1037\t∑ \n1038\tπ \n1039\t∈ \n1040\tℬ \n1041\t− \n1042\t1 \n1043\t\n1044\t​ \n1045\t( \n1046\t𝐲 \n1047\t) \n1048\t\n1049\t∏ \n1050\tt \n1051\t= \n1052\t1 \n1053\t\n1054\tT \n1055\t\n1056\t𝐪 \n1057\tt \n1058\t\n1059\t​ \n1060\t( \n1061\tπ \n1062\tt \n1063\t\n1064\t) \n1065\t\n1066\t, \n1067\t\n1068\t\\mathcal{L}_{\\text{ctc}}=-\\log\\!\\!\\sum_{\\pi\\in\\mathcal{B}^{-1}(\\mathbf{y})}\\;\\prod_{t=1}^{T}\\mathbf{q}_{t}(\\pi_{t}), \n1069\t\n1070\t(9) \n1071\t\n1072\twhere ℬ \n1073\t\\mathcal{B} \n1074\t\n1075\tcollapses repeats and removes blanks. Feasibility needs T \n1076\t≥ \n1077\tM \n1078\t\n1079\tT\\geq M \n1080\t\n1081\t, so we cap targets to the number of real audio tokens. The full objective is \n1082\t\n1083\tℒ \n1084\t= \n1085\tℒ \n1086\tdiff \n1087\t\n1088\t+ \n1089\tλ \n1090\tar \n1091\t\n1092\t​ \n1093\tℒ \n1094\tar \n1095\t\n1096\t+ \n1097\tλ \n1098\tctc \n1099\t\n1100\t​ \n1101\tℒ \n1102\tctc \n1103\t\n1104\t. \n1105\t\n1106\t\\mathcal{L}=\\mathcal{L}_{\\text{diff}}+\\lambda_{\\text{ar}}\\,\\mathcal{L}_{\\text{ar}}+\\lambda_{\\text{ctc}}\\,\\mathcal{L}_{\\text{ctc}}. \n1107\t\n1108\t(10) \n1109\t\n1110\tLow-rank adaptation. \n1111\tWe add LoRA adapters (Hu et al., 2022 \n1112\t) \n1113\tof rank 16 and scaling 32 on the query, key, value, and output projections of both the encoder and the decoder self-attention. The encoder adapters let the model fold audio into the cache, and the decoder adapters let it attend to that cache during denoising. The experts and the vision tower stay frozen. The projector and the adapters together are 42.3M trainable parameters, which is 0.16 percent of the backbone. \n1114\t\n1115\t3.6 \n1116\tWhy grounding fails, and how CTC fixes it \n1117\tWith only the diffusion and autoregressive losses, training stalled in a way that took us a while to understand. The curves fell for a few hundred steps and then went flat. The diffusion loss settled near 8 and the autoregressive loss sat around 4.5, close to chance, and neither moved for thousands of steps. \n1118\t\n1119\tBoth losses reach the projector only through attention over the audio positions. Let α \n1120\tt \n1121\t\n1122\t\\alpha_{t} \n1123\t\n1124\tbe the aggregate attention mass the model places on audio token t \n1125\tt \n1126\t\n1127\t. To first order the gradient the attention-routed losses send to 𝐮 \n1128\tt \n1129\t\n1130\t\\mathbf{u}_{t} \n1131\t\n1132\tscales with that mass, \n1133\t\n1134\t∂ \n1135\tℒ \n1136\tdiff \n1137\t\n1138\t∂ \n1139\t𝐮 \n1140\tt \n1141\t\n1142\t∼ \n1143\tα \n1144\tt \n1145\t\n1146\t​ \n1147\tW \n1148\tV \n1149\t⊤ \n1150\t\n1151\t​ \n1152\t𝜹 \n1153\tt \n1154\t\n1155\t, \n1156\t\n1157\t\\frac{\\partial\\mathcal{L}_{\\text{diff}}}{\\partial\\mathbf{u}_{t}}\\;\\sim\\;\\alpha_{t}\\,W_{V}^{\\!\\top}\\boldsymbol{\\delta}_{t}, \n1158\t\n1159\t(11) \n1160\t\n1161\twhere 𝜹 \n1162\tt \n1163\t\n1164\t\\boldsymbol{\\delta}_{t} \n1165\t\n1166\tis the backpropagated error at the attended positions and W \n1167\tV \n1168\t\n1169\tW_{V} \n1170\t\n1171\tthe value projection. At initialization 𝐮 \n1172\tt \n1173\t\n1174\t\\mathbf{u}_{t} \n1175\t\n1176\tis random, the frozen prior explains the visible clean context, and the model learns α \n1177\tt \n1178\t\n1179\t→ \n1180\t0 \n1181\t\n1182\t\\alpha_{t}\\to 0 \n1183\t\n1184\t, which sends this gradient to zero. The gradient that would raise α \n1185\tt \n1186\t\n1187\t\\alpha_{t} \n1188\t\n1189\tis also small, because 𝐮 \n1190\tt \n1191\t\n1192\t\\mathbf{u}_{t} \n1193\t\n1194\tcarries nothing worth attending to. Both directions vanish at the same fixed point. The projector and the attention each wait for the other to move first. \n1195\t\n1196\tCTC removes the α \n1197\tt \n1198\t\n1199\t\\alpha_{t} \n1200\t\n1201\tfactor. Its gradient to the projector is the linear-head cross-entropy gradient composed with the CTC forward-backward occupancy 𝝆 \n1202\tt \n1203\t\n1204\t\\boldsymbol{\\rho}_{t} \n1205\t\n1206\t, the posterior probability of each label at frame t \n1207\tt \n1208\t\n1209\t, \n1210\t\n1211\t∂ \n1212\tℒ \n1213\tctc \n1214\t\n1215\t∂ \n1216\t𝐮 \n1217\tt \n1218\t\n1219\t= \n1220\tW \n1221\tU \n1222\t⊤ \n1223\t\n1224\t​ \n1225\t( \n1226\t𝐪 \n1227\tt \n1228\t\n1229\t− \n1230\t𝝆 \n1231\tt \n1232\t\n1233\t) \n1234\t\n1235\t, \n1236\t\n1237\t\\frac{\\partial\\mathcal{L}_{\\text{ctc}}}{\\partial\\mathbf{u}_{t}}=W_{U}^{\\!\\top}\\big(\\mathbf{q}_{t}-\\boldsymbol{\\rho}_{t}\\big), \n1238\t\n1239\t(12) \n1240\t\n1241\twhich is nonzero whatever the attention does. It pushes 𝐮 \n1242\tt \n1243\t\n1244\t\\mathbf{u}_{t} \n1245\t\n1246\tinto the region of embedding space where W \n1247\tU \n1248\t\n1249\t​ \n1250\t𝐮 \n1251\tt \n1252\t\n1253\tW_{U}\\mathbf{u}_{t} \n1254\t\n1255\tpredicts transcript tokens, with no attention required. Once 𝐮 \n1256\tt \n1257\t\n1258\t\\mathbf{u}_{t} \n1259\t\n1260\tcarries content, α \n1261\tt \n1262\t\n1263\t\\alpha_{t} \n1264\t\n1265\tgrows and the gradients in Eq. 11 \n1266\t\n1267\trevive. Adding the term broke the plateau on our first attempt: the CTC loss fell from 24 to 8.6 in about 300 steps and held-out token accuracy climbed off the floor. The CTC head is a training-time scaffold, which we drop at inference so that recognition runs entirely through the diffusion decoder. \n1268\t\n1269\t3.7 \n1270\tInference as parallel denoising \n1271\tWhisper’s encoder is fixed to a thirty second window, so longer audio is split at silence. We take the quietest short frame near a thirteen second target inside a three second search window and cut there, so no word is split and the non-overlapping segments concatenate with no stitching. Each segment is denoised on a canvas of L \n1272\t= \n1273\t192 \n1274\t\n1275\tL{=}192 \n1276\t\n1277\tslots by Algorithm 1 \n1278\t\n1279\t. \n1280\t\n1281\tThe sampler is the base model’s uniform-diffusion process, conditioned on audio. Each step recomputes the denoiser logits over the whole canvas, accepts the positions whose predictive entropy H \n1282\t​ \n1283\t( \n1284\t𝐩 \n1285\ti \n1286\t\n1287\t) \n1288\t\n1289\tH(\\mathbf{p}_{i}) \n1290\t\n1291\tfalls below a bound η \n1292\t\\eta \n1293\t\n1294\t, and renoises the rest to fresh uniform tokens. A linear temperature schedule anneals from 0.8 down to 0.4, self-conditioning (Chen et al., 2023 \n1295\t) \n1296\tfeeds the previous prediction forward, and a stability-and-confidence criterion stops early once the canvas settles. Optional classifier-free guidance (Ho and Salimans, 2022 \n1297\t) \n1298\tcombines a conditional pass with an unconditional pass that hides the audio cache, ℓ \n1299\t= \n1300\tℓ \n1301\tu \n1302\t\n1303\t+ \n1304\tw \n1305\t​ \n1306\t( \n1307\tℓ \n1308\tc \n1309\t\n1310\t− \n1311\tℓ \n1312\tu \n1313\t\n1314\t) \n1315\t\n1316\t\\boldsymbol{\\ell}=\\boldsymbol{\\ell}^{u}+w(\\boldsymbol{\\ell}^{c}-\\boldsymbol{\\ell}^{u}) \n1317\t\n1318\t, to sharpen the effect of the audio without retraining. A short post-processing pass removes repeated words and n-grams, the canvas-fill artifacts a diffusion decoder produces when the transcript is shorter than the canvas. \n1319\t\n1320\tAlgorithm 1 \n1321\t\n1322\tAudio-conditioned parallel denoising \n1323\t1: \n1324\tinput: \n1325\taudio 𝐚 \n1326\t\\mathbf{a} \n1327\t\n1328\t, prompt 𝐜 \n1329\t\\mathbf{c} \n1330\t\n1331\t, steps S \n1332\tS \n1333\t\n1334\t, guidance w \n1335\tw \n1336\t\n1337\t, bound η \n1338\t\\eta \n1339\t\n1340\t2: \n1341\t𝐊 \n1342\t← \n1343\tEnc \n1344\tθ \n1345\t\n1346\t​ \n1347\t( \n1348\tscatter \n1349\t​ \n1350\t( \n1351\tEmb \n1352\t​ \n1353\t( \n1354\t𝐜 \n1355\t) \n1356\t\n1357\t, \n1358\t𝒫 \n1359\tϕ \n1360\t\n1361\t​ \n1362\t( \n1363\t𝐚 \n1364\t) \n1365\t\n1366\t) \n1367\t\n1368\t) \n1369\t\n1370\t\\mathbf{K}\\leftarrow\\mathrm{Enc}_{\\theta}(\\mathrm{scatter}(\\mathrm{Emb}(\\mathbf{c}),\\,\\mathcal{P}_{\\phi}(\\mathbf{a}))) \n1371\t\n1372\t3: \n1373\t𝐱 \n1374\t← \n1375\t\n1376\t\\mathbf{x}\\leftarrow \n1377\t\n1378\tuniform random in 𝒱 \n1379\tL \n1380\t\n1381\t\\mathcal{V}^{L} \n1382\t\n1383\t4: \n1384\tfor \n1385\ts \n1386\t= \n1387\t1 \n1388\t\n1389\ts=1 \n1390\t\n1391\tto \n1392\tS \n1393\tS \n1394\t\n1395\tdo \n1396\t\n1397\t5: \n1398\tℓ \n1399\t← \n1400\tσ \n1401\tτ \n1402\t\n1403\t​ \n1404\t( \n1405\tW \n1406\tU \n1407\t\n1408\t​ \n1409\tDec \n1410\tθ \n1411\t\n1412\t​ \n1413\t( \n1414\t𝐱 \n1415\t, \n1416\t𝐊 \n1417\t) \n1418\t\n1419\t) \n1420\t\n1421\t\\boldsymbol{\\ell}\\leftarrow\\sigma_{\\tau}\\!\\big(W_{U}\\,\\mathrm{Dec}_{\\theta}(\\mathbf{x},\\mathbf{K})\\big) \n1422\t\n1423\t6: \n1424\tif \n1425\tw \n1426\t≠ \n1427\t1 \n1428\t\n1429\tw\\neq 1 \n1430\t\n1431\tthen \n1432\t\n1433\t7: \n1434\tℓ \n1435\tu \n1436\t\n1437\t← \n1438\tσ \n1439\tτ \n1440\t\n1441\t​ \n1442\t( \n1443\tW \n1444\tU \n1445\t\n1446\t​ \n1447\tDec \n1448\tθ \n1449\t\n1450\t​ \n1451\t( \n1452\t𝐱 \n1453\t, \n1454\t𝐊 \n1455\t∖ \n1456\taudio \n1457\t\n1458\t) \n1459\t\n1460\t) \n1461\t\n1462\t\\boldsymbol{\\ell}^{u}\\leftarrow\\sigma_{\\tau}\\!\\big(W_{U}\\,\\mathrm{Dec}_{\\theta}(\\mathbf{x},\\mathbf{K}^{\\setminus\\text{audio}})\\big) \n1463\t\n1464\t8: \n1465\tℓ \n1466\t← \n1467\tℓ \n1468\tu \n1469\t\n1470\t+ \n1471\tw \n1472\t​ \n1473\t( \n1474\tℓ \n1475\t− \n1476\tℓ \n1477\tu \n1478\t\n1479\t) \n1480\t\n1481\t\\boldsymbol{\\ell}\\leftarrow\\boldsymbol{\\ell}^{u}+w\\,(\\boldsymbol{\\ell}-\\boldsymbol{\\ell}^{u}) \n1482\t\n1483\t9: \n1484\tend \n1485\tif \n1486\t\n1487\t10: \n1488\t𝐩 \n1489\t← \n1490\tsoftmax \n1491\t​ \n1492\t( \n1493\tℓ \n1494\t/ \n1495\ttemp \n1496\t\n1497\t​ \n1498\t( \n1499\ts \n1500\t) \n1501\t\n1502\t) \n1503\t\n1504\t\\mathbf{p}\\leftarrow\\mathrm{softmax}(\\boldsymbol{\\ell}/\\text{temp}(s)) \n1505\t\n1506\t; 𝐱 \n1507\t^ \n1508\t\n1509\t∼ \n1510\tMultinomial \n1511\t​ \n1512\t( \n1513\t𝐩 \n1514\t) \n1515\t\n1516\t\\hat{\\mathbf{x}}\\sim\\mathrm{Multinomial}(\\mathbf{p}) \n1517\t\n1518\t11: \n1519\tkeep x \n1520\t^ \n1521\t\n1522\ti \n1523\t\n1524\t\\hat{x}_{i} \n1525\t\n1526\twhere H \n1527\t​ \n1528\t( \n1529\t𝐩 \n1530\ti \n1531\t\n1532\t) \n1533\t\n1534\t< \n1535\tη \n1536\t\n1537\tH(\\mathbf{p}_{i})<\\eta \n1538\t\n1539\t; renoise the rest to fresh uniform tokens \n1540\t12: \n1541\tif \n1542\targ \n1543\t⁡ \n1544\tmax \n1545\t⁡ \n1546\tℓ \n1547\t\n1548\t\\arg\\max\\boldsymbol{\\ell} \n1549\t\n1550\tstable and confident then break \n1551\t\n1552\t13: \n1553\tend \n1554\tfor \n1555\t\n1556\t14: \n1557\treturn \n1558\targ \n1559\t⁡ \n1560\tmax \n1561\t⁡ \n1562\tℓ \n1563\t\n1564\t\\arg\\max\\boldsymbol{\\ell} \n1565\t\n1566\t, decoded up to eos \n1567\t\n1568\tCost. \n1569\tAutoregressive decoding needs M \n1570\tM \n1571\t\n1572\tsequential decoder passes to emit M \n1573\tM \n1574\t\n1575\ttokens (Vaswani et al., 2017 \n1576\t) \n1577\t. Diffusion decoding needs at most S \n1578\tS \n1579\t\n1580\tpasses over the whole canvas in parallel, plus one encoder pass, and doubles the decoder passes only when guidance is on. The cost is set by S \n1581\tS \n1582\t\n1583\tand is independent of the transcript length M \n1584\tM \n1585\t\n1586\t. With S \n1587\t≈ \n1588\t8 \n1589\t≪ \n1590\tM \n1591\t\n1592\tS\\approx 8\\ll M \n1593\t\n1594\t, and the flat accuracy curve of Table 4 \n1595\t\n1596\t, this is the source of the speedup. \n1597\t\n1598\t4 \n1599\tExperimental Setup \n1600\tData. \n1601\tStage one, we train the English model on the 100 hour clean subset of LibriSpeech (Panayotov et al., 2015 \n1602\t) \n1603\t. The multilingual model warm-starts from the English checkpoint and continues on FLEURS (Conneau et al., 2023 \n1604\t) \n1605\tacross six languages, English, German, French, Spanish, Hindi, and Mandarin. A further stage adds VoxPopuli parliamentary speech (Wang et al., 2021 \n1606\t) \n1607\t. The model has seen roughly 219 hours of audio in total. \n1608\t\n1609\tOptimization. \n1610\tWe use AdamW with a learning rate of 1 \n1611\t​ \n1612\te \n1613\t\n1614\t− \n1615\t3 \n1616\t\n1617\t1\\mathrm{e}{-3} \n1618\t\n1619\t, betas of 0.9 and 0.95, and weight decay of 0.01, with 100 warmup steps and a cosine decay to one tenth of the peak. We clip gradients at norm 1.0. The backbone runs in bfloat16 and the projector in float32 for stable updates. Batches hold 4 utterances with 2 gradient accumulation steps, reduced to 2 and 6 on the longer VoxPopuli material. All runs use a single H100. \n1620\t\n1621\tEvaluation. \n1622\tWe report word error rate with the Whisper text normalizer applied to both reference and hypothesis, which is the Open-ASR and Artificial Analysis convention. For Hindi and Mandarin we report character error rate, because word error rate penalizes scripts whose word boundaries do not match the reference segmentation and overstates the error. We also report throughput as a multiple of real time. \n1623\t\n1624\tConfiguration. \n1625\tTable 1 \n1626\t\n1627\tlists the settings used for the reported runs. \n1628\t\n1629\tSetting \n1630\tValue \n1631\t\n1632\tOptimizer \n1633\tAdamW ( \n1634\t0.9 \n1635\t, \n1636\t0.95 \n1637\t) \n1638\t\n1639\t(0.9,0.95) \n1640\t\n1641\t, weight decay 0.01 \n1642\t0.01 \n1643\t\n1644\tLearning rate \n1645\t1 \n1646\t​ \n1647\te \n1648\t\n1649\t− \n1650\t3 \n1651\t\n1652\t1\\mathrm{e}{-3} \n1653\t\n1654\t, 100 warmup, cosine to 0.1 \n1655\t× \n1656\t\n1657\t0.1\\times \n1658\t\n1659\tGradient clip \n1660\t1.0 \n1661\t1.0 \n1662\t\n1663\tBatch × \n1664\t\\times \n1665\t\n1666\taccum \n1667\t4 \n1668\t× \n1669\t2 \n1670\t\n1671\t4\\times 2 \n1672\t\n1673\t(Libri/FLEURS), 2 \n1674\t× \n1675\t6 \n1676\t\n1677\t2\\times 6 \n1678\t\n1679\t(VoxPopuli) \n1680\t\n1681\tPrecision \n1682\tbf16 backbone, fp32 projector \n1683\t\n1684\tCanvas L \n1685\tL \n1686\t\n1687\t256 train, 192 inference \n1688\t\n1689\tSubsample / tokens \n1690\t8 \n1691\t× \n1692\t\n1693\t8\\times \n1694\t\n1695\t/ T \n1696\t= \n1697\t188 \n1698\t\n1699\tT{=}188 \n1700\t\n1701\tLoRA \n1702\tr \n1703\t= \n1704\t16 \n1705\t\n1706\tr{=}16 \n1707\t\n1708\t, α \n1709\t= \n1710\t32 \n1711\t\n1712\t\\alpha{=}32 \n1713\t\n1714\t, dropout 0.05 \n1715\t0.05 \n1716\t\n1717\t, enc+dec attn \n1718\t\n1719\tLoss weights \n1720\tλ \n1721\tar \n1722\t\n1723\t= \n1724\t1 \n1725\t\n1726\t\\lambda_{\\text{ar}}{=}1 \n1727\t\n1728\t, λ \n1729\tctc \n1730\t\n1731\t= \n1732\t1 \n1733\t\n1734\t\\lambda_{\\text{ctc}}{=}1 \n1735\t\n1736\t, w \n1737\t​ \n1738\t( \n1739\tγ \n1740\t) \n1741\t\n1742\t= \n1743\t1 \n1744\t\n1745\tw(\\gamma){=}1 \n1746\t\n1747\tInference \n1748\t8 steps, η \n1749\t= \n1750\t0.1 \n1751\t\n1752\t\\eta{=}0.1 \n1753\t\n1754\t, guidance w \n1755\t= \n1756\t1 \n1757\t\n1758\tw{=}1 \n1759\t\n1760\t, temp 0.8 \n1761\t→ \n1762\t0.4 \n1763\t\n1764\t0.8\\!\\to\\!0.4 \n1765\t\n1766\tTable 1: \n1767\tTraining and inference configuration for the reported runs. \n1768\t\n1769\t5 \n1770\tResults \n1771\t5.1 \n1772\tEnglish recognition and grounding dynamics \n1773\tOn LibriSpeech test-clean, English word error rate walked down over ten epochs, from roughly 90 percent early in training to about 50 percent, then to 14.6 percent, and finally to 6.6 percent at the last checkpoint ( n \n1774\t= \n1775\t100 \n1776\t\n1777\tn{=}100 \n1778\t\n1779\ttest-clean utterances). The two intermediate points come from small held-out samples and are approximate; the final number is on the full evaluation set. This is single-digit word error rate from a frozen 26B backbone, a frozen Whisper encoder, and about 42M trainable parameters. \n1780\t\n1781\tGrounding was not monotone in the metrics. Token accuracy reached 0.50 and CTC loss kept falling while the model still said nothing useful. A manual decode at 0.4 epochs showed the greedy CTC output emitting the unigram prior, the most frequent tokens in frequency order such as “the of to he”, with no relation to the audio, even though the loss curve looked healthy. Only repeated exposure over many passes brought the projector and the attention into a configuration that actually transcribes, so we ran a manual decode every half epoch. As training progressed the outputs moved from repeated fragments to fluent text with occasional acoustic slips, such as “tents” for “tense”, the error profile of a model transcribing from the audio rather than falling back on its text prior. \n1782\t\n1783\tTable 2 \n1784\t\n1785\tshows the same run in numbers. The autoregressive loss stays near chance and token accuracy hovers around 0.4 to 0.5 through the first epoch, then both move sharply once the projector grounds. Without the CTC term the same configuration did not ground within the compute we ran, which is the failure Section 3.6 \n1786\t\n1787\tanalyzes; we observed this during development rather than as a controlled ablation. \n1788\t\n1789\tStep \n1790\tVal AR loss \n1791\tVal token acc \n1792\t\n1793\t25 \n1794\t5.01 \n1795\t0.42 \n1796\t\n1797\t300 \n1798\t4.62 \n1799\t0.44 \n1800\t\n1801\t900 \n1802\t4.45 \n1803\t0.50 \n1804\t\n1805\t2808 (ep. 2) \n1806\t0.34 \n1807\t0.85 \n1808\t\n1809\tTable 2: \n1810\tGrounding dynamics on a held-out set of about 32 utterances. The autoregressive loss stays near chance and token accuracy plateaus while the model is ungrounded, then both improve sharply. Over the same span the CTC loss falls from 24 to 8.6 and then below 0.1. \n1811\t\n1812\t5.2 \n1813\tMultilingual recognition \n1814\tWarm-starting from English and training on FLEURS gave one adapter covering all six languages. We report the three for which we ran held-out evaluation, English, Hindi, and Mandarin. German, French, and Spanish are in the training mix but were not separately evaluated here. Adding VoxPopuli traded a small amount of read-speech accuracy for a gain on conversational and accented audio, a movement along the accuracy frontier rather than a free improvement. Table 3 \n1815\t\n1816\treports the adapter under the Whisper normalizer. \n1817\t\n1818\tBenchmark \n1819\tMetric \n1820\tScore \n1821\tn \n1822\tn \n1823\t\n1824\tFLEURS English \n1825\tWER \n1826\t15.7% \n1827\t150 \n1828\t\n1829\tVoxPopuli English \n1830\tWER \n1831\t18.5% \n1832\t1000 \n1833\t\n1834\tFLEURS Hindi \n1835\tCER \n1836\t15.8% \n1837\t300 \n1838\t\n1839\tFLEURS Mandarin \n1840\tCER \n1841\t29.6% \n1842\t300 \n1843\t\n1844\tTable 3: \n1845\tMultilingual adapter, Whisper-normalized, with evaluation set sizes n \n1846\tn \n1847\t\n1848\t. Mandarin word error rate reads 40 percent under word segmentation, while the character error rate on the same transcripts is 29.6 percent. \n1849\t\n1850\t5.3 \n1851\tParallel decoding \n1852\tBecause the decoder refines the entire canvas at once, transcription cost is set by the number of denoising steps and not by the length of the transcript. Table 4 \n1853\t\n1854\tsweeps the step count on FLEURS English. The curve is close to flat. Moving from 8 steps to 48 buys about half a point of word error rate and costs roughly three times the latency. The model converges in about eight parallel passes. For a ten second clip this is on the order of one second of model time, and it does not grow with how much the speaker says. \n1855\t\n1856\tSteps \n1857\tFLEURS-en WER \n1858\tSpeed \n1859\t\n1860\t8 \n1861\t15.7% \n1862\t14.9 × \n1863\t\\times \n1864\t\n1865\t16 \n1866\t15.6% \n1867\t10.3 × \n1868\t\\times \n1869\t\n1870\t32 \n1871\t15.2% \n1872\t6.5 × \n1873\t\\times \n1874\t\n1875\t48 \n1876\t15.6% \n1877\t4.7 × \n1878\t\\times \n1879\t\n1880\tTable 4: \n1881\tWord error rate and throughput as a multiple of real time against the number of denoising steps (FLEURS English, n \n1882\t= \n1883\t150 \n1884\t\n1885\tn{=}150 \n1886\t\n1887\t). \n1888\t\n1889\t5.4 \n1890\tComparison with diffusion and autoregressive systems \n1891\tTable 5 \n1892\t\n1893\tplaces our LibriSpeech test-clean result beside other diffusion and non-autoregressive systems. These are the numbers reported in the respective papers, not controlled reruns, and the systems differ in encoder, training data, tokenization, and decoding, so the table is context rather than a head-to-head comparison. We place our result next to TransFusion (Baas et al., 2022 \n1894\t) \n1895\tand Whisfusion (Kwon et al., 2025 \n1896\t) \n1897\tfor reference, not to claim a controlled win. \n1898\t\n1899\tModel \n1900\tApproach \n1901\tWER \n1902\t\n1903\tTransFusion \n1904\tmultinomial diffusion \n1905\t∼ \n1906\t\\sim \n1907\t\n1908\t6–7% \n1909\t\n1910\tWhisfusion \n1911\tmasked diffusion \n1912\t8.3% \n1913\t\n1914\tOurs \n1915\tfrozen diffusion LM \n1916\t6.6% \n1917\t\n1918\tTable 5: \n1919\tDiffusion and non-autoregressive speech recognition on LibriSpeech test-clean. Baseline numbers are as reported by their authors under differing encoders, data, and decoding, and are not controlled reruns; only our row ( n \n1920\t= \n1921\t100 \n1922\t\n1923\tn{=}100 \n1924\t\n1925\t) is measured in this work. TransFusion is a character-level proof of concept. \n1926\t\n1927\tAgainst autoregressive Whisper, which remains the strongest baseline, our model trails, as Table 6 \n1928\t\n1929\tshows. All numbers use the Whisper normalizer. The gap is largest on FLEURS and VoxPopuli and smallest on LibriSpeech, the one domain where we had a hundred clean hours. \n1930\t\n1931\tBenchmark \n1932\tOurs \n1933\tW-small \n1934\tW-large-v3 \n1935\t\n1936\tLibriSpeech clean \n1937\t6.6% \n1938\t∼ \n1939\t\\sim \n1940\t\n1941\t3.4% \n1942\t∼ \n1943\t\\sim \n1944\t\n1945\t2.0% \n1946\t\n1947\tFLEURS-en \n1948\t15.7% \n1949\t∼ \n1950\t\\sim \n1951\t\n1952\t9–10% \n1953\t∼ \n1954\t\\sim \n1955\t\n1956\t4–5% \n1957\t\n1958\tVoxPopuli-en \n1959\t18.5% \n1960\t∼ \n1961\t\\sim \n1962\t\n1963\t9–11% \n1964\t∼ \n1965\t\\sim \n1966\t\n1967\t7–10% \n1968\t\n1969\tTable 6: \n1970\tContext against autoregressive Whisper. The Whisper columns are published ranges, not controlled reruns; only the Ours column is measured here (LibriSpeech n \n1971\t= \n1972\t100 \n1973\t\n1974\tn{=}100 \n1975\t\n1976\t, FLEURS-en n \n1977\t= \n1978\t150 \n1979\t\n1980\tn{=}150 \n1981\t\n1982\t, VoxPopuli-en n \n1983\t= \n1984\t1000 \n1985\t\n1986\tn{=}1000 \n1987\t\n1988\t). \n1989\t\n1990\t5.5 \n1991\tWhat is the bottleneck \n1992\tWe ran ablations to locate the source of the residual error, because the answer decides whether the method is broken or simply undertrained. We ruled out one suspect at a time. \n1993\t\n1994\tFirst, encoder quality. We swapped the Whisper-small front end for Whisper-large-v3 and retrained on the same 100 hour set. Word error rate at matched data moved from 14.75 percent at three epochs to 13.15 at six and 8.95 at eight, which is roughly even with the small-encoder run at the same data scale. A stronger encoder did not move the floor at this data budget, so the encoder is not the current limit. \n1995\t\n1996\tSecond, audio resolution. We reduced the subsample factor below eight to give the projector more audio tokens per second. This regressed to 44.7 percent word error rate rather than improving, so token resolution is not the limit either, and the eight-fold subsample is not starving the decoder. \n1997\t\n1998\tThird, decode steps. The step sweep in Table 4 \n1999\t\n2000\tis flat, so the sampler is not leaving accuracy on the table. \n2001\t\n2002\tWith encoder quality, resolution, and step count ruled out, the most likely remaining explanation is data scale and adapter alignment. Whisper-large-v3 was trained on a few million hours and Whisper-small on about 680 thousand. This model has seen roughly 219 hours, three orders of magnitude fewer, and it already reached 6.6 percent on the single domain where it had a hundred clean hours. The frontend ablation points the same way, since a stronger encoder did not help at this data budget, which is what one expects when the bottleneck is data rather than features. The evidence is consistent with a data bottleneck rather than a broken method, but we cannot establish this without a scaling curve, which we leave to future work. \n2003\t\n2004\t6 \n2005\tRelated Work \n2006\tHow speech recognition decodes. \n2007\tEnd-to-end recognition grew from two ideas. Connectionist temporal classification aligns a frame sequence to a shorter label sequence without explicit segmentation (Graves et al., 2006 \n2008\t) \n2009\t. Attention-based sequence-to-sequence models instead let a decoder attend over the encoded audio and spell the transcript (Chan et al., 2016 \n2010\t) \n2011\t, a pattern the transformer generalized (Vaswani et al., 2017 \n2012\t) \n2013\t. Most progress since then has come from stronger encoders, including self-supervised representations (Baevski et al., 2020 \n2014\t) \n2015\tand convolution-augmented transformers (Gulati et al., 2020 \n2016\t) \n2017\t, and from scale and weak supervision (Radford et al., 2023 \n2018\t) \n2019\t. In all of these the transcript is produced one token at a time. \n2020\t\n2021\tNon-autoregressive and diffusion text generation. \n2022\tParallel generation began with non-autoregressive translation, which emits the whole target at once (Gu et al., 2018 \n2023\t) \n2024\t. Diffusion models, developed for continuous data (Sohl-Dickstein et al., 2015 \n2025\t; Ho et al., 2020 \n2026\t) \n2027\t, were brought to language both by embedding tokens in a continuous space (Li et al., 2022 \n2028\t; Gong et al., 2023 \n2029\t) \n2030\tand by defining the corruption directly on discrete tokens (Austin et al., 2021 \n2031\t; Lou et al., 2024 \n2032\t) \n2033\t. Self-conditioning improved discrete diffusion by feeding the previous prediction back into the next step (Chen et al., 2023 \n2034\t) \n2035\t, a technique our sampler uses. Large masked-diffusion language models now reach quality competitive with autoregressive models of similar size (Nie et al., 2025 \n2036\t) \n2037\t. DiffusionGemma sits in this family but corrupts toward uniform random tokens rather than an absorbing mask. \n2038\t\n2039\tDiffusion speech recognition and audio language models. \n2040\tTwo systems put diffusion decoding directly on speech. TransFusion transcribed characters with multinomial diffusion as a proof of concept (Baas et al., 2022 \n2041\t) \n2042\t, and Whisfusion trained a masked-diffusion decoder over frozen Whisper features (Kwon et al., 2025 \n2043\t) \n2044\t. Both build that decoder from scratch, whereas we reuse one that already exists. Separately, a large body of work gives new modalities to frozen or lightly adapted language models through a trained connector, for vision (Liu et al., 2023 \n2045\t) \n2046\tand for audio (Chu et al., 2023 \n2047\t; Rubenstein et al., 2023 \n2048\t) \n2049\t, often on top of open model families such as Gemma (Gemma Team, 2024 \n2050\t) \n2051\t. Our work joins these two threads. We reuse an off-the-shelf diffusion language model with no new decoder, connect a frozen speech encoder through a projector and low-rank adapters (Hu et al., 2022 \n2052\t) \n2053\t, ground it with connectionist temporal classification (Graves et al., 2006 \n2054\t) \n2055\t, decode with uniform random-token diffusion rather than absorbing masks, and train one adapter on six languages. \n2056\t\n2057\t7 \n2058\tLimitations \n2059\tThe model trails autoregressive Whisper on every benchmark we tested, by the largest margin on multilingual read speech. The evidence points to data scale as the cause rather than architecture, but that remains a hypothesis until we train on substantially more audio. The Whisper encoder fixes the input window at thirty seconds, so real streaming is not possible and long audio is handled by silence segmentation, which can err when speech has no clear pauses. The diffusion decoder can produce repetition artifacts on short utterances, which we currently remove with a post-processing pass rather than at the source. Finally, our comparisons to Whisper use published ranges under the same normalizer rather than a single controlled re-run of every baseline, so the Whisper columns should be read as reference points rather than exact head-to-head numbers. \n2060\t\n2061\t8 \n2062\tConclusion \n2063\tA frozen language model can learn to hear if the audio projector is supervised directly rather than only through attention. Loss curves and token accuracy will look healthy well before the model is actually grounded, so manual decoding matters during training. Once grounded, diffusion decoding makes the length of what a speaker said stop mattering for cost, because recognition converges in about eight parallel steps. The grounding recipe, the CTC unlock, and the diffusion decoder all work today; what the model still lacks is exposure to more hours of audio. \n2064\t\n2065\tReferences \n2066\tAustin et al. (2021) \n2067\tJacob Austin, Daniel D. Johnson, Jonathan Ho, Daniel Tarlow, and Rianne van den Berg. 2021. \n2068\tStructured denoising diffusion models in discrete state-spaces. \n2069\tIn Advances in Neural Information Processing Systems \n2070\t. arXiv:2107.03006. \n2071\t\n2072\tBaas et al. (2022) \n2073\tMatthew Baas, Kevin Eloff, and Herman Kamper. 2022. \n2074\tTransFusion: Transcribing speech with multinomial diffusion \n2075\t. \n2076\tIn Southern African Conference for Artificial Intelligence Research (SACAIR) \n2077\t. arXiv:2210.07677. \n2078\t\n2079\tBaevski et al. (2020) \n2080\tAlexei Baevski, Henry Zhou, Abdelrahman Mohamed, and Michael Auli. 2020. \n2081\twav2vec 2.0: A framework for self-supervised learning of speech representations. \n2082\tIn Advances in Neural Information Processing Systems \n2083\t. arXiv:2006.11477. \n2084\t\n2085\tChan et al. (2016) \n2086\tWilliam Chan, Navdeep Jaitly, Quoc V. Le, and Oriol Vinyals. 2016. \n2087\tListen, attend and spell: A neural network for large vocabulary conversational speech recognition. \n2088\tIn IEEE International Conference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal Processing (ICASSP) \n2089\t. arXiv:1508.01211. \n2090\t\n2091\tChen et al. (2023) \n2092\tTing Chen, Ruixiang Zhang, and Geoffrey Hinton. 2023. \n2093\tAnalog bits: Generating discrete data using diffusion models with self-conditioning. \n2094\tIn International Conference on Learning Representations \n2095\t. arXiv:2208.04202. \n2096\t\n2097\tChu et al. (2023) \n2098\tYunfei Chu, Jin Xu, Xiaohuan Zhou, Qian Yang, Shiliang Zhang, Zhijie Yan, Chang Zhou, and Jingren Zhou. 2023. \n2099\tQwen-Audio: Advancing universal audio understanding via unified large-scale audio-language models. \n2100\tComputing Research Repository \n2101\t, arXiv:2311.07919. \n2102\t\n2103\tConneau et al. (2023) \n2104\tAlexis Conneau, Min Ma, Simran Khanuja, Yu Zhang, Vera Axelrod, Siddharth Dalmia, Jason Riesa, Clara Rivera, and Ankur Bapna. 2023. \n2105\tFLEURS: Few-shot learning evaluation of universal representations of speech. \n2106\tIn IEEE Spoken Language Technology Workshop (SLT) \n2107\t. arXiv:2205.12446. \n2108\t\n2109\tGemma Team (2024) \n2110\tGemma Team. 2024. \n2111\tGemma: Open models based on Gemini research and technology. \n2112\tComputing Research Repository \n2113\t, arXiv:2403.08295. \n2114\t\n2115\tGong et al. (2023) \n2116\tShansan Gong, Mukai Li, Jiangtao Feng, Zhiyong Wu, and Lingpeng Kong. 2023. \n2117\tDiffuSeq: Sequence to sequence text generation with diffusion models. \n2118\tIn International Conference on Learning Representations \n2119\t. arXiv:2210.08933. \n2120\t\n2121\tGraves et al. (2006) \n2122\tAlex Graves, Santiago Fernández, Faustino Gomez, and Jürgen Schmidhuber. 2006. \n2123\tConnectionist temporal classification: Labelling unsegmented sequence data with recurrent neural networks \n2124\t. \n2125\tIn Proceedings of the 23rd International Conference on Machine Learning \n2126\t, pages 369–376. \n2127\t\n2128\tGu et al. (2018) \n2129\tJiatao Gu, James Bradbury, Caiming Xiong, Victor O.K. Li, and Richard Socher. 2018. \n2130\tNon-autoregressive neural machine translation. \n2131\tIn International Conference on Learning Representations \n2132\t. arXiv:1711.02281. \n2133\t\n2134\tGulati et al. (2020) \n2135\tAnmol Gulati, James Qin, Chung-Cheng Chiu, Niki Parmar, Yu Zhang, Jiahui Yu, Wei Han, Shibo Wang, Zhengdong Zhang, Yonghui Wu, and Ruoming Pang. 2020. \n2136\tConformer: Convolution-augmented transformer for speech recognition. \n2137\tIn Interspeech \n2138\t. arXiv:2005.08100. \n2139\t\n2140\tHo et al. (2020) \n2141\tJonathan Ho, Ajay Jain, and Pieter Abbeel. 2020. \n2142\tDenoising diffusion probabilistic models. \n2143\tIn Advances in Neural Information Processing Systems \n2144\t. arXiv:2006.11239. \n2145\t\n2146\tHo and Salimans (2022) \n2147\tJonathan Ho and Tim Salimans. 2022. \n2148\tClassifier-free diffusion guidance. \n2149\tComputing Research Repository \n2150\t, arXiv:2207.12598. \n2151\t\n2152\tHu et al. (2022) \n2153\tEdward J. Hu, Yelong Shen, Phillip Wallis, Zeyuan Allen-Zhu, Yuanzhi Li, Shean Wang, Lu Wang, and Weizhu Chen. 2022. \n2154\tLoRA: Low-rank adaptation of large language models. \n2155\tIn International Conference on Learning Representations \n2156\t. arXiv:2106.09685. \n2157\t\n2158\tKwon et al. (2025) \n2159\tTaeyoun Kwon, Junhyuk Ahn, Taegeun Yun, Heeju Jwa, Yoonchae Choi, Siwon Park, Jongchan Kim, Hyungon Ryu, Hyuk-Jae Lee, and Nam-Joon Kim. 2025. \n2160\tWhisfusion: Parallel ASR decoding with masked diffusion. \n2161\tComputing Research Repository \n2162\t, arXiv:2508.07048. \n2163\t\n2164\tLi et al. (2022) \n2165\tXiang Lisa Li, John Thickstun, Ishaan Gulrajani, Percy Liang, and Tatsunori B. Hashimoto. 2022. \n2166\tDiffusion-LM improves controllable text generation. \n2167\tIn Advances in Neural Information Processing Systems \n2168\t. arXiv:2205.14217. \n2169\t\n2170\tLiu et al. (2023) \n2171\tHaotian Liu, Chunyuan Li, Qingyang Wu, and Yong Jae Lee. 2023. \n2172\tVisual instruction tuning. \n2173\tIn Advances in Neural Information Processing Systems \n2174\t. arXiv:2304.08485. \n2175\t\n2176\tLou et al. (2024) \n2177\tAaron Lou, Chenlin Meng, and Stefano Ermon. 2024. \n2178\tDiscrete diffusion modeling by estimating the ratios of the data distribution. \n2179\tIn Proceedings of the 41st International Conference on Machine Learning \n2180\t. arXiv:2310.16834. \n2181\t\n2182\tNie et al. (2025) \n2183\tShen Nie, Fengqi Zhu, Zebin You, Xiaolu Zhang, Jingyang Ou, Jun Hu, Jun Zhou, Yankai Lin, Ji-Rong Wen, and Chongxuan Li. 2025. \n2184\tLarge language diffusion models. \n2185\tComputing Research Repository \n2186\t, arXiv:2502.09992. \n2187\t\n2188\tPanayotov et al. (2015) \n2189\tVassil Panayotov, Guoguo Chen, Daniel Povey, and Sanjeev Khudanpur. 2015. \n2190\tLibrispeech: An ASR corpus based on public domain audio books \n2191\t. \n2192\tIn IEEE International Conference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal Processing (ICASSP) \n2193\t, pages 5206–5210. \n2194\t\n2195\tRadford et al. (2023) \n2196\tAlec Radford, Jong Wook Kim, Tao Xu, Greg Brockman, Christine McLeavey, and Ilya Sutskever. 2023. \n2197\tRobust speech recognition via large-scale weak supervision. \n2198\tIn Proceedings of the 40th International Conference on Machine Learning \n2199\t. arXiv:2212.04356. \n2200\t\n2201\tRubenstein et al. (2023) \n2202\tPaul K. Rubenstein, Chulayuth Asawaroengchai, Duc Dung Nguyen, Ankur Bapna, Zalán Borsos, and others. 2023. \n2203\tAudioPaLM: A large language model that can speak and listen. \n2204\tComputing Research Repository \n2205\t, arXiv:2306.12925. \n2206\t\n2207\tSohl-Dickstein et al. (2015) \n2208\tJascha Sohl-Dickstein, Eric A. Weiss, Niru Maheswaranathan, and Surya Ganguli. 2015. \n2209\tDeep unsupervised learning using nonequilibrium thermodynamics. \n2210\tIn Proceedings of the 32nd International Conference on Machine Learning \n2211\t, pages 2256–2265. arXiv:1503.03585. \n2212\t\n2213\tVaswani et al. (2017) \n2214\tAshish Vaswani, Noam Shazeer, Niki Parmar, Jakob Uszkoreit, Llion Jones, Aidan N. Gomez, Łukasz Kaiser, and Illia Polosukhin. 2017. \n2215\tAttention is all you need. \n2216\tIn Advances in Neural Information Processing Systems \n2217\t. arXiv:1706.03762. \n2218\t\n2219\tWang et al. (2021) \n2220\tChanghan Wang, Morgane Rivière, Ann Lee, Anne Wu, Chaitanya Talnikar, Daniel Haziza, Mary Williamson, Juan Pino, and Emmanuel Dupoux. 2021. \n2221\tVoxPopuli: A large-scale multilingual speech corpus for representation learning, semi-supervised learning and interpretation \n2222\t. \n2223\tIn Proceedings of the 59th Annual Meeting of the Association for Computational Linguistics \n2224\t, pages 993–1003. \n2225\t\n2226\tMajor funding support from \n2227\t\n2228\t\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "b040b9fa-6567-43eb-b7b3-aaa9e6036043", "uuid": "46958a25-002c-448a-a44a-0dd2c4f9da57", "timestamp": "2026-07-15T05:39:15.523Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/paper_text_2607.13013.txt", "content": "Audio-Native Speech Recognition with a Frozen Discrete-Diffusion Language Model \n\nTitle: \nContent selection saved. Describe the issue below: \nDescription: \n\narXiv is now an independent nonprofit! \nLearn more \n× \n\nLicense: arXiv.org perpetual non-exclusive license \narXiv:2607.13013v1 [cs.AI] 14 Jul 2026 \n\nAudio-Native Speech Recognition with a Frozen Discrete-Diffusion Language Model \nHarsha Vardhan Khurdula 1 \n\nAbhinav Kumar Singh 2 \n\nYoeven D Khemlani 2 \n\nVineet Agarwal 2 \n\nInterfaze AI San Francisco, CA, USA {harsha, abhinav, yoeven, vineet}@interfaze.ai \n\nAbstract \nAutomatic speech recognition is dominated by autoregressive decoders that emit one token at a time. We ask whether a discrete diffusion language model can transcribe speech instead, refining a whole transcript in parallel over a small number of denoising steps. We train an audio-native interface for DiffusionGemma, a 26B mixture-of-experts model that generates text by uniform, random-token discrete diffusion rather than the absorbing-mask scheme common to recent diffusion language models. A frozen Whisper encoder supplies acoustic features, a lightweight projector maps them into the model embedding space, and low-rank adapters let the frozen backbone attend to the new modality. \nAbout 42M parameters are trained, which is 0.16 percent of the backbone. We find that the natural training objectives fail to ground the audio, because their gradient reaches the projector only through attention that has already dismissed it. A connectionist temporal classification loss applied through the frozen output head breaks this deadlock. The resulting model reaches 6.6 percent word error rate on LibriSpeech test-clean, transcribes in roughly eight parallel steps regardless of utterance length, and uses a single adapter trained on six languages, which we evaluate here on English, Hindi, and Mandarin. \n\nAudio-Native Speech Recognition with a Frozen Discrete-Diffusion Language Model \n\nHarsha Vardhan Khurdula 1 \n\nAbhinav Kumar Singh 2 \n\nYoeven D Khemlani 2 \n\nVineet Agarwal 2 \n\nInterfaze AI \n\nSan Francisco, CA, USA \n\n{harsha, abhinav, yoeven, vineet}@interfaze.ai \n\n1 \nIntroduction \nSpeech recognition has been decoded the same way for a long time. An encoder reads the audio, and an attention decoder spells the transcript one token at a time, feeding each token back to itself to produce the next (Chan et al., 2016 \n; Radford et al., 2023 \n) \n. The encoders have grown very strong, but the decoder is serial by construction, so a thirty second clip costs a few hundred sequential forward passes no matter how much hardware is available. Diffusion language models decode differently, starting from a canvas of noise and refining the whole sequence in parallel over a small number of denoising steps; they now reach quality competitive with autoregressive models of similar size (Nie et al., 2025 \n) \n. The natural question is whether speech can be transcribed the same way, so that the cost of recognition is set by the number of denoising steps and not by the length of the transcript. \n\nTwo systems have shown that diffusion can transcribe. TransFusion denoised character sequences with multinomial diffusion (Baas et al., 2022 \n) \n, and Whisfusion trained a masked-diffusion decoder on top of frozen Whisper features (Kwon et al., 2025 \n) \n. Both train a decoder specifically for the task, and both are English only. We ask a different question: can an existing, general-purpose diffusion language model be taught to hear, so that recognition runs through its own decoder with no new decoder trained at all? \n\nWe take DiffusionGemma, an open-weight 26B mixture-of-experts model that generates text by discrete diffusion (does not have audio support), and give it a native audio input. We keep the backbone frozen. We add a frozen Whisper encoder as an acoustic feature extractor (Radford et al., 2023 \n) \n, a small trainable projector that maps those features into the model embedding space, and low-rank adapters (Hu et al., 2022 \n) \nso the frozen model can learn to attend to the new modality. The projector-into-language-model recipe follows the connectors that gave sight and hearing to text-only models (Liu et al., 2023 \n; Chu et al., 2023 \n; Rubenstein et al., 2023 \n) \n, applied here for the first time to a diffusion decoder. Only about 42M parameters train, which is 0.16 percent of the backbone. The result reaches 6.6 percent word error rate on LibriSpeech test-clean, converges in about eight parallel steps regardless of utterance length, and uses a single adapter trained on six languages. \n\nThe challenge lied in grounding, a frozen language model has never seen a spectrogram, so its embedding space has no notion of formants or phonemes, and the two obvious training objectives both route their signal through cross-attention. If attention has already decided the audio is noise, no gradient reaches the projector to make it useful, and the projector stays noise, which in turn gives attention no reason to change. We break this deadlock with a connectionist temporal classification loss applied directly through the frozen output head, which forces the audio embeddings to be linearly predictive of the transcript without asking attention to trust them first. \n\nOur contributions are the following. \n• \nAn audio-native pathway for a frozen discrete-diffusion language model, trained only through a projector and low-rank adapters, with no decoder trained from scratch. \n\n• \nA diagnosis of the grounding failure and a direct-supervision fix that breaks the projector and attention deadlock in a few hundred steps. \n\n• \nAn empirical study of the accuracy and speed of diffusion decoding for speech, including a step count sweep that shows recognition cost decoupled from transcript length. \n\n• \nA single adapter trained on six languages (English, German, French, Spanish, Hindi, Mandarin) and evaluated here on English, Hindi, and Mandarin, together with an analysis of where it trails autoregressive Whisper and why. \n\n2 \nBackground \n2.1 \nThe diffusion backbone \nDiffusionGemma is a 26B mixture-of-experts model with 128 experts, top-8 routing, and roughly 4B active parameters per token. It has 30 transformer layers, a hidden size of 2816, and a vocabulary of 262144. It generates text by discrete diffusion rather than autoregression. \n\nMost recent diffusion language models use an absorbing state, where corruption replaces tokens with a special <mask> \nsymbol and generation fills masks in (Austin et al., 2021 \n; Lou et al., 2024 \n; Nie et al., 2025 \n) \n. DiffusionGemma instead uses uniform, random-token diffusion. It starts from a fixed-length canvas, up to 256 slots, filled with random tokens drawn from the vocabulary. At each denoising step the model reads the whole canvas at once, keeps the low-entropy predictions it is confident about, and renoises the remaining positions back to fresh random tokens. After a few steps the noise anneals into text (Figure 1 \n\n). Training mirrors this process. A clean sequence is corrupted by replacing a fraction γ \n\\gamma \n\nof positions with uniform random tokens, and the model is trained to recover the originals at the corrupted positions. We formalize the process in Section 3.4 \n\n. \n\nFigure 1: \nUniform discrete diffusion in DiffusionGemma. Generation starts from a canvas of random vocabulary tokens and, over a few steps, keeps the confident predictions and renoises the rest until the canvas anneals into text. There is no absorbing mask state. \n\n2.2 \nEncoder-decoder structure \nArchitecturally the model is an encoder-decoder with tied transformer weights. The encoder reads the prompt causally into a read-only key-value cache. The decoder refines the canvas with bidirectional self-attention while cross-attending to that cache. Multimodal inputs are injected by scattering projected features into placeholder token positions of the encoder input embeddings. The existing vision path uses an image token identifier for this. Out of the box the model accepts text, images, and video, and produces text. It does not accept audio and providing that modality is one of our key contributions in our work. \n\n2.3 \nConnecting an encoder to a language model \nA frozen language model can be given a new input modality by training a small connector that maps features from a modality encoder into the model embedding space, while the backbone stays fixed or is only lightly adapted. This recipe added vision to text-only models through a projector over a vision encoder (Liu et al., 2023 \n) \n, and audio to language models through speech encoders and adapters (Chu et al., 2023 \n; Rubenstein et al., 2023 \n) \n, usually on top of open model families such as Gemma (Gemma Team, 2024 \n) \n. Our audio pathway follows the same pattern. What is new is the decoder it feeds. Every connector we are aware of feeds an autoregressive model, whereas here the connector conditions a diffusion decoder that produces the transcript in parallel, which changes both how the model must be grounded and how it decodes. \n\n3 \nMethod \nFigure 2: \nThe audio-native pathway. A frozen Whisper encoder produces acoustic features, a trainable projector maps them to T \n= \n188 \n\nT{=}188 \n\naudio tokens in the model embedding space, and these are scattered into the placeholder positions of the encoder prompt. The frozen DiffusionGemma encoder reads the prompt into a key-value cache, and the decoder denoises the transcript canvas in parallel while attending to that cache. Three losses train the projector and the low-rank adapters. The diffusion loss and the autoregressive auxiliary loss route through attention, and the connectionist temporal classification loss is applied directly through the frozen output head. \n\n3.1 \nNotation and setup \nLet 𝒱 \n\\mathcal{V} \n\nbe the vocabulary with V \n= \n| \n𝒱 \n| \n\n= \n262 \n\n, \n144 \n\nV=|\\mathcal{V}|=262{,}144 \n\n. A transcript is a token sequence 𝐲 \n= \n( \ny \n1 \n\n, \n… \n, \ny \nM \n\n) \n\n\\mathbf{y}=(y_{1},\\dots,y_{M}) \n\n. We write it onto a fixed canvas of length L \nL \n\n(we use L \n= \n256 \n\nL{=}256 \n\nin training and L \n= \n192 \n\nL{=}192 \n\nat inference) as the clean target 𝐱 \n0 \n\n= \n( \n𝐲 \n, \neos \n, \npad \n, \n… \n) \n\n∈ \n𝒱 \nL \n\n\\mathbf{x}_{0}=(\\mathbf{y},\\textsc{eos},\\textsc{pad},\\dots)\\in\\mathcal{V}^{L} \n\n. The audio is a log-mel spectrogram 𝐦 \n∈ \nℝ \n80 \n× \n3000 \n\n\\mathbf{m}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{80\\times 3000} \n\n, since Whisper pads or trims to thirty seconds. We keep the DiffusionGemma backbone and the Whisper encoder frozen and train only a projector 𝒫 \nϕ \n\n\\mathcal{P}_{\\phi} \n\nand low-rank adapters θ \n\\theta \n\n. We write σ \nτ \n\n​ \n( \nz \n) \n\n= \nτ \n​ \ntanh \n⁡ \n( \nz \n/ \nτ \n\n) \n\n\\sigma_{\\tau}(z)=\\tau\\tanh(z/\\tau) \n\nfor the final logit softcap with τ \n= \n30 \n\n\\tau{=}30 \n\n, and W \nU \n\n∈ \nℝ \nV \n× \nd \n\nW_{U}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{V\\times d} \n\nfor the frozen tied output head, with model width d \n= \n2816 \n\nd{=}2816 \n\n. The overall architecture is shown in Figure 2 \n\n. \n\n3.2 \nAudio pathway \nIn our first attempt, we skipped the acoustic encoder entirely. Some unified Gemma models project raw waveforms straight into the embedding space, so we fed the model short audio frames and let the backbone infer the acoustics to test this approach. And it failed completely, as a frozen language model that has never seen audio cannot build an acoustic front end from gradient signal alone, and a shallow projector cannot do feature extraction on its own. Word error rate plateaued near 94 percent while the model produced fluent text unrelated to the audio. \n\nThe working design uses a frozen Whisper-small encoder (Radford et al., 2023 \n) \nas a feature extractor, not as a decoder. It carries the acoustic modeling that self-supervised representations (Baevski et al., 2020 \n) \nand convolution-augmented transformers (Gulati et al., 2020 \n) \nestablished, which is the map from sound to linguistic features a frozen text model cannot learn on its own. The encoder produces 𝐚 \n∈ \nℝ \nF \n× \nd \nw \n\n\\mathbf{a}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{F\\times d_{w}} \n\nwith F \n= \n1500 \n\nF{=}1500 \n\nframes and d \nw \n\n= \n768 \n\nd_{w}{=}768 \n\n. The projector maps these to audio tokens 𝐮 \n∈ \nℝ \nT \n× \nd \n\n\\mathbf{u}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{T\\times d} \n\n, \n\n𝐡 \n( \n0 \n) \n\n\\displaystyle\\mathbf{h}^{(0)} \n\n= \nGELU \n​ \n( \n𝐚 \n​ \nW \nin \n\n) \n\n, \n\n\\displaystyle=\\mathrm{GELU}(\\mathbf{a}\\,W_{\\text{in}}), \n\n(1) \n\n𝐡 \n( \nl \n) \n\n\\displaystyle\\mathbf{h}^{(l)} \n\n= \nGELU \n\n​ \n( \nConv1d \n( \nl \n) \n\n​ \n( \n𝐡 \n( \nl \n− \n1 \n\n) \n\n) \n\n) \n\n, \nl \n= \n1 \n, \n2 \n, \n3 \n\n, \n\n\\displaystyle=\\mathrm{GELU}\\!\\big(\\mathrm{Conv1d}^{(l)}(\\mathbf{h}^{(l-1)})\\big),\\quad l=1,2,3, \n\n(2) \n\n𝐮 \n\\displaystyle\\mathbf{u} \n\n= \nLN \n\n​ \n( \n𝐡 \n( \n3 \n) \n\n​ \nW \nout \n\n) \n\n, \n\n\\displaystyle=\\mathrm{LN}\\!\\big(\\mathbf{h}^{(3)}\\,W_{\\text{out}}\\big), \n\n(3) \n\nwith W \nin \n\n∈ \nℝ \nd \nw \n\n× \nd \nh \n\nW_{\\text{in}}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{d_{w}\\times d_{h}} \n\n, W \nout \n\n∈ \nℝ \nd \nh \n\n× \nd \n\nW_{\\text{out}}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{d_{h}\\times d} \n\n, hidden width d \nh \n\n= \n1280 \n\nd_{h}{=}1280 \n\n, and convolutions of kernel 3, stride 2, and padding 1. Each convolution maps a length n \nn \n\nto ⌊ \n( \nn \n− \n1 \n\n) \n\n/ \n2 \n\n⌋ \n\n+ \n1 \n\n\\lfloor(n-1)/2\\rfloor+1 \n\n, so 1500 \n→ \n750 \n→ \n375 \n→ \n188 \n\n1500\\to 750\\to 375\\to 188 \n\nand T \n= \n188 \n\nT{=}188 \n\n, about 6.25 tokens per second. The projector, together with the adapters introduced below, is the only trained part of the model. \n\n3.3 \nConditioning the diffusion decoder on audio \nWe build a fixed-length prompt \n\n[BOS] \n​ \ninstr \n​ \n[BOA] \n​ \n( \n<audio> \n) \n\n× \nT \n\n​ \n[EOA] \n\n, \n\n\\texttt{[BOS]}\\ \\text{instr}\\ \\texttt{[BOA]}\\ \\big(\\texttt{<audio>}\\big)^{\\!\\times T}\\ \\texttt{[EOA]}, \n\nwith audio placeholder positions 𝒜 \n\\mathcal{A} \n\n, | \n𝒜 \n| \n\n= \nT \n\n|\\mathcal{A}|{=}T \n\n. We embed the prompt and overwrite the placeholders with the projected audio tokens, \n\n𝐄 \nj \n\n= \n{ \n𝐮 \nρ \n​ \n( \nj \n) \n\nj \n∈ \n𝒜 \n\n, \n\nEmb \n​ \n( \nc \nj \n\n) \n\notherwise, \n\n\\mathbf{E}_{j}=\\begin{cases}\\mathbf{u}_{\\rho(j)}&j\\in\\mathcal{A},\\\\[2.0pt]\n\\mathrm{Emb}(c_{j})&\\text{otherwise,}\\end{cases} \n\n(4) \n\nwhere ρ \n\\rho \n\nindexes projector rows, reusing the scatter mechanism the vision path uses. The frozen encoder, with adapters θ \n\\theta \n\n, reads this into a key-value cache 𝐊 \n= \nEnc \nθ \n\n​ \n( \n𝐄 \n) \n\n\\mathbf{K}=\\mathrm{Enc}_{\\theta}(\\mathbf{E}) \n\n, and the decoder cross-attends to 𝐊 \n\\mathbf{K} \n\nwhile denoising, as in Eq. 6 \n\n. The prompt length is constant because T \nT \n\nis fixed. For clips shorter than thirty seconds we zero the attention mask on the silence-pad audio positions so the encoder ignores them. The canvas holds the transcript, an end-of-sequence marker, and padding, and is the decoder target 𝐱 \n0 \n\n\\mathbf{x}_{0} \n\n. \n\n3.4 \nUniform discrete diffusion \nWith the audio in the cache, we can state the generation process. Unlike the absorbing-state schemes used by most diffusion language models (Austin et al., 2021 \n; Lou et al., 2024 \n; Nie et al., 2025 \n) \n, DiffusionGemma corrupts toward uniform random tokens rather than a mask. A single scalar γ \n∈ \n[ \n0 \n, \n1 \n] \n\n\\gamma\\in[0,1] \n\nsets the corruption level and plays the role a timestep plays in continuous diffusion. Corruption acts independently at each position, \n\nq \n​ \n( \nx \nγ \ni \n\n= \nk \n∣ \nx \n0 \ni \n\n; \nγ \n\n) \n\n= \n( \n1 \n− \nγ \n\n) \n\n​ \n1 \n​ \n[ \nk \n= \nx \n0 \ni \n\n] \n\n+ \nγ \nV \n\n, \n\nq(x_{\\gamma}^{i}=k\\mid x_{0}^{i};\\gamma)=(1-\\gamma)\\,\\mathbf{1}[k=x_{0}^{i}]+\\frac{\\gamma}{V}, \n\n(5) \n\nwhich is the cumulative uniform D3PM kernel Q \n¯ \n\nγ \n\n= \n( \n1 \n− \nγ \n\n) \n\n​ \nI \n\n+ \nγ \nV \n\n​ \n𝟏𝟏 \n⊤ \n\n\\bar{Q}_{\\gamma}=(1-\\gamma)\\,I+\\tfrac{\\gamma}{V}\\mathbf{1}\\mathbf{1}^{\\!\\top} \n\n(Austin et al., 2021 \n) \n. Equivalently, draw b \ni \n\n∼ \nBernoulli \n​ \n( \nγ \n) \n\nb_{i}\\sim\\mathrm{Bernoulli}(\\gamma) \n\nand r \ni \n\n∼ \nUnif \n​ \n( \n𝒱 \n) \n\nr_{i}\\sim\\mathrm{Unif}(\\mathcal{V}) \n\nand set x \nγ \ni \n\n= \n( \n1 \n− \nb \ni \n\n) \n\n​ \nx \n0 \ni \n\n+ \nb \ni \n\n​ \nr \ni \n\nx_{\\gamma}^{i}=(1-b_{i})\\,x_{0}^{i}+b_{i}\\,r_{i} \n\n. There is no special mask symbol, so a corrupted position holds a real, random vocabulary token. \n\nThe model is trained in the 𝐱 \n0 \n\n\\mathbf{x}_{0} \n\nparameterization. Given the corrupted canvas and the audio conditioning 𝐜 \n\\mathbf{c} \n\ncarried by the cache 𝐊 \n\\mathbf{K} \n\n, it predicts the clean token at each position, \n\np \nθ \n, \nϕ \n\n​ \n( \nx \n0 \ni \n\n∣ \n𝐱 \nγ \n\n, \n𝐜 \n\n) \n\n\\displaystyle p_{\\theta,\\phi}(x_{0}^{i}\\mid\\mathbf{x}_{\\gamma},\\mathbf{c}) \n\n= \nsoftmax \n\n​ \n( \nσ \nτ \n\n​ \n( \nW \nU \n\n​ \n𝐡 \ni \n\n) \n\n) \n\n, \n\n\\displaystyle=\\mathrm{softmax}\\!\\big(\\sigma_{\\tau}(W_{U}\\,\\mathbf{h}_{i})\\big), \n\n(6) \n\n𝐡 \n\\displaystyle\\mathbf{h} \n\n= \nDec \nθ \n\n​ \n( \n𝐱 \nγ \n\n, \n𝐊 \n) \n\n. \n\n\\displaystyle=\\mathrm{Dec}_{\\theta}(\\mathbf{x}_{\\gamma},\\mathbf{K}). \n\n3.5 \nTraining objectives \nThree losses share one projector and one set of adapters. \n\nDiffusion loss. \nThis is the model’s own objective, the reweighted 𝐱 \n0 \n\n\\mathbf{x}_{0} \n\n-prediction surrogate of the discrete-diffusion variational bound (Austin et al., 2021 \n; Ho et al., 2020 \n) \n. Let 𝒞 \n\\mathcal{C} \n\nbe the corrupted, non-pad positions. Taking the expectation over γ \n∼ \nUnif \n​ \n( \n0 \n, \n1 \n) \n\n\\gamma\\sim\\mathrm{Unif}(0,1) \n\n, the data, and the corruption, \n\nℒ \ndiff \n\n= \n𝔼 \n\n​ \n[ \nw \n​ \n( \nγ \n) \n\n| \n𝒞 \n| \n\n​ \n∑ \ni \n∈ \n𝒞 \n\n− \nlog \n⁡ \np \nθ \n, \nϕ \n\n​ \n( \nx \n0 \ni \n\n∣ \n𝐱 \nγ \n\n, \n𝐜 \n\n) \n\n] \n\n, \n\n\\mathcal{L}_{\\text{diff}}=\\mathbb{E}\\!\\left[\\frac{w(\\gamma)}{|\\mathcal{C}|}\\sum_{i\\in\\mathcal{C}}-\\log p_{\\theta,\\phi}(x_{0}^{i}\\mid\\mathbf{x}_{\\gamma},\\mathbf{c})\\right], \n\n(7) \n\nwith an optional importance weight w \n​ \n( \nγ \n) \n\n∈ \n{ \n1 \n, \n1 \n/ \nγ \n\n} \n\nw(\\gamma)\\in\\{1,\\,1/\\gamma\\} \n\n. The loss is applied only at corrupted positions. Because the objective is bidirectional and the frozen text prior explains much of the visible clean context, the gradient asking the model to use audio is diluted (Section 3.6 \n\n). We therefore force γ \n= \n1 \n\n\\gamma{=}1 \n\non a fraction of batches, where the audio is the only source of information. \n\nAutoregressive auxiliary loss. \nThe encoder is causal, so we can teacher-force the transcript through it and read a standard next-token loss, \n\nℒ \nar \n\n= \n𝔼 \n​ \n[ \n1 \nM \n\n​ \n∑ \ni \n= \n1 \n\nM \n\n− \nlog \n⁡ \nsoftmax \n\n​ \n( \nσ \nτ \n\n​ \n( \nW \nU \n\n​ \n𝐠 \ni \n\n) \n\n) \n\ny \ni \n\n] \n\n, \n\n\\mathcal{L}_{\\text{ar}}=\\mathbb{E}\\Big[\\frac{1}{M}\\sum_{i=1}^{M}-\\log\\,\\mathrm{softmax}\\!\\big(\\sigma_{\\tau}(W_{U}\\mathbf{g}_{i})\\big)_{y_{i}}\\Big], \n\n(8) \n\nwhere 𝐠 \ni \n\n\\mathbf{g}_{i} \n\nis the encoder state that predicts y \ni \n\ny_{i} \n\nfrom 𝐲 \n\n< \ni \n\n\\mathbf{y}_{<i} \n\nand the audio. Because the encoder shares weights with the diffusion decoder and reads the same audio tokens, this dense per-token gradient transfers to parallel denoising. \n\nCTC loss. \nWe decode the projector rows directly through the frozen output head, with no softcap, and align them to the transcript with connectionist temporal classification (Graves et al., 2006 \n) \n. With per-frame distributions 𝐪 \nt \n\n= \nsoftmax \n​ \n( \nW \nU \n\n​ \n𝐮 \nt \n\n) \n\n\\mathbf{q}_{t}=\\mathrm{softmax}(W_{U}\\mathbf{u}_{t}) \n\nand the blank symbol at index 0, \n\nℒ \nctc \n\n= \n− \nlog \n\n​ \n∑ \nπ \n∈ \nℬ \n− \n1 \n\n​ \n( \n𝐲 \n) \n\n∏ \nt \n= \n1 \n\nT \n\n𝐪 \nt \n\n​ \n( \nπ \nt \n\n) \n\n, \n\n\\mathcal{L}_{\\text{ctc}}=-\\log\\!\\!\\sum_{\\pi\\in\\mathcal{B}^{-1}(\\mathbf{y})}\\;\\prod_{t=1}^{T}\\mathbf{q}_{t}(\\pi_{t}), \n\n(9) \n\nwhere ℬ \n\\mathcal{B} \n\ncollapses repeats and removes blanks. Feasibility needs T \n≥ \nM \n\nT\\geq M \n\n, so we cap targets to the number of real audio tokens. The full objective is \n\nℒ \n= \nℒ \ndiff \n\n+ \nλ \nar \n\n​ \nℒ \nar \n\n+ \nλ \nctc \n\n​ \nℒ \nctc \n\n. \n\n\\mathcal{L}=\\mathcal{L}_{\\text{diff}}+\\lambda_{\\text{ar}}\\,\\mathcal{L}_{\\text{ar}}+\\lambda_{\\text{ctc}}\\,\\mathcal{L}_{\\text{ctc}}. \n\n(10) \n\nLow-rank adaptation. \nWe add LoRA adapters (Hu et al., 2022 \n) \nof rank 16 and scaling 32 on the query, key, value, and output projections of both the encoder and the decoder self-attention. The encoder adapters let the model fold audio into the cache, and the decoder adapters let it attend to that cache during denoising. The experts and the vision tower stay frozen. The projector and the adapters together are 42.3M trainable parameters, which is 0.16 percent of the backbone. \n\n3.6 \nWhy grounding fails, and how CTC fixes it \nWith only the diffusion and autoregressive losses, training stalled in a way that took us a while to understand. The curves fell for a few hundred steps and then went flat. The diffusion loss settled near 8 and the autoregressive loss sat around 4.5, close to chance, and neither moved for thousands of steps. \n\nBoth losses reach the projector only through attention over the audio positions. Let α \nt \n\n\\alpha_{t} \n\nbe the aggregate attention mass the model places on audio token t \nt \n\n. To first order the gradient the attention-routed losses send to 𝐮 \nt \n\n\\mathbf{u}_{t} \n\nscales with that mass, \n\n∂ \nℒ \ndiff \n\n∂ \n𝐮 \nt \n\n∼ \nα \nt \n\n​ \nW \nV \n⊤ \n\n​ \n𝜹 \nt \n\n, \n\n\\frac{\\partial\\mathcal{L}_{\\text{diff}}}{\\partial\\mathbf{u}_{t}}\\;\\sim\\;\\alpha_{t}\\,W_{V}^{\\!\\top}\\boldsymbol{\\delta}_{t}, \n\n(11) \n\nwhere 𝜹 \nt \n\n\\boldsymbol{\\delta}_{t} \n\nis the backpropagated error at the attended positions and W \nV \n\nW_{V} \n\nthe value projection. At initialization 𝐮 \nt \n\n\\mathbf{u}_{t} \n\nis random, the frozen prior explains the visible clean context, and the model learns α \nt \n\n→ \n0 \n\n\\alpha_{t}\\to 0 \n\n, which sends this gradient to zero. The gradient that would raise α \nt \n\n\\alpha_{t} \n\nis also small, because 𝐮 \nt \n\n\\mathbf{u}_{t} \n\ncarries nothing worth attending to. Both directions vanish at the same fixed point. The projector and the attention each wait for the other to move first. \n\nCTC removes the α \nt \n\n\\alpha_{t} \n\nfactor. Its gradient to the projector is the linear-head cross-entropy gradient composed with the CTC forward-backward occupancy 𝝆 \nt \n\n\\boldsymbol{\\rho}_{t} \n\n, the posterior probability of each label at frame t \nt \n\n, \n\n∂ \nℒ \nctc \n\n∂ \n𝐮 \nt \n\n= \nW \nU \n⊤ \n\n​ \n( \n𝐪 \nt \n\n− \n𝝆 \nt \n\n) \n\n, \n\n\\frac{\\partial\\mathcal{L}_{\\text{ctc}}}{\\partial\\mathbf{u}_{t}}=W_{U}^{\\!\\top}\\big(\\mathbf{q}_{t}-\\boldsymbol{\\rho}_{t}\\big), \n\n(12) \n\nwhich is nonzero whatever the attention does. It pushes 𝐮 \nt \n\n\\mathbf{u}_{t} \n\ninto the region of embedding space where W \nU \n\n​ \n𝐮 \nt \n\nW_{U}\\mathbf{u}_{t} \n\npredicts transcript tokens, with no attention required. Once 𝐮 \nt \n\n\\mathbf{u}_{t} \n\ncarries content, α \nt \n\n\\alpha_{t} \n\ngrows and the gradients in Eq. 11 \n\nrevive. Adding the term broke the plateau on our first attempt: the CTC loss fell from 24 to 8.6 in about 300 steps and held-out token accuracy climbed off the floor. The CTC head is a training-time scaffold, which we drop at inference so that recognition runs entirely through the diffusion decoder. \n\n3.7 \nInference as parallel denoising \nWhisper’s encoder is fixed to a thirty second window, so longer audio is split at silence. We take the quietest short frame near a thirteen second target inside a three second search window and cut there, so no word is split and the non-overlapping segments concatenate with no stitching. Each segment is denoised on a canvas of L \n= \n192 \n\nL{=}192 \n\nslots by Algorithm 1 \n\n. \n\nThe sampler is the base model’s uniform-diffusion process, conditioned on audio. Each step recomputes the denoiser logits over the whole canvas, accepts the positions whose predictive entropy H \n​ \n( \n𝐩 \ni \n\n) \n\nH(\\mathbf{p}_{i}) \n\nfalls below a bound η \n\\eta \n\n, and renoises the rest to fresh uniform tokens. A linear temperature schedule anneals from 0.8 down to 0.4, self-conditioning (Chen et al., 2023 \n) \nfeeds the previous prediction forward, and a stability-and-confidence criterion stops early once the canvas settles. Optional classifier-free guidance (Ho and Salimans, 2022 \n) \ncombines a conditional pass with an unconditional pass that hides the audio cache, ℓ \n= \nℓ \nu \n\n+ \nw \n​ \n( \nℓ \nc \n\n− \nℓ \nu \n\n) \n\n\\boldsymbol{\\ell}=\\boldsymbol{\\ell}^{u}+w(\\boldsymbol{\\ell}^{c}-\\boldsymbol{\\ell}^{u}) \n\n, to sharpen the effect of the audio without retraining. A short post-processing pass removes repeated words and n-grams, the canvas-fill artifacts a diffusion decoder produces when the transcript is shorter than the canvas. \n\nAlgorithm 1 \n\nAudio-conditioned parallel denoising \n1: \ninput: \naudio 𝐚 \n\\mathbf{a} \n\n, prompt 𝐜 \n\\mathbf{c} \n\n, steps S \nS \n\n, guidance w \nw \n\n, bound η \n\\eta \n\n2: \n𝐊 \n← \nEnc \nθ \n\n​ \n( \nscatter \n​ \n( \nEmb \n​ \n( \n𝐜 \n) \n\n, \n𝒫 \nϕ \n\n​ \n( \n𝐚 \n) \n\n) \n\n) \n\n\\mathbf{K}\\leftarrow\\mathrm{Enc}_{\\theta}(\\mathrm{scatter}(\\mathrm{Emb}(\\mathbf{c}),\\,\\mathcal{P}_{\\phi}(\\mathbf{a}))) \n\n3: \n𝐱 \n← \n\n\\mathbf{x}\\leftarrow \n\nuniform random in 𝒱 \nL \n\n\\mathcal{V}^{L} \n\n4: \nfor \ns \n= \n1 \n\ns=1 \n\nto \nS \nS \n\ndo \n\n5: \nℓ \n← \nσ \nτ \n\n​ \n( \nW \nU \n\n​ \nDec \nθ \n\n​ \n( \n𝐱 \n, \n𝐊 \n) \n\n) \n\n\\boldsymbol{\\ell}\\leftarrow\\sigma_{\\tau}\\!\\big(W_{U}\\,\\mathrm{Dec}_{\\theta}(\\mathbf{x},\\mathbf{K})\\big) \n\n6: \nif \nw \n≠ \n1 \n\nw\\neq 1 \n\nthen \n\n7: \nℓ \nu \n\n← \nσ \nτ \n\n​ \n( \nW \nU \n\n​ \nDec \nθ \n\n​ \n( \n𝐱 \n, \n𝐊 \n∖ \naudio \n\n) \n\n) \n\n\\boldsymbol{\\ell}^{u}\\leftarrow\\sigma_{\\tau}\\!\\big(W_{U}\\,\\mathrm{Dec}_{\\theta}(\\mathbf{x},\\mathbf{K}^{\\setminus\\text{audio}})\\big) \n\n8: \nℓ \n← \nℓ \nu \n\n+ \nw \n​ \n( \nℓ \n− \nℓ \nu \n\n) \n\n\\boldsymbol{\\ell}\\leftarrow\\boldsymbol{\\ell}^{u}+w\\,(\\boldsymbol{\\ell}-\\boldsymbol{\\ell}^{u}) \n\n9: \nend \nif \n\n10: \n𝐩 \n← \nsoftmax \n​ \n( \nℓ \n/ \ntemp \n\n​ \n( \ns \n) \n\n) \n\n\\mathbf{p}\\leftarrow\\mathrm{softmax}(\\boldsymbol{\\ell}/\\text{temp}(s)) \n\n; 𝐱 \n^ \n\n∼ \nMultinomial \n​ \n( \n𝐩 \n) \n\n\\hat{\\mathbf{x}}\\sim\\mathrm{Multinomial}(\\mathbf{p}) \n\n11: \nkeep x \n^ \n\ni \n\n\\hat{x}_{i} \n\nwhere H \n​ \n( \n𝐩 \ni \n\n) \n\n< \nη \n\nH(\\mathbf{p}_{i})<\\eta \n\n; renoise the rest to fresh uniform tokens \n12: \nif \narg \n⁡ \nmax \n⁡ \nℓ \n\n\\arg\\max\\boldsymbol{\\ell} \n\nstable and confident then break \n\n13: \nend \nfor \n\n14: \nreturn \narg \n⁡ \nmax \n⁡ \nℓ \n\n\\arg\\max\\boldsymbol{\\ell} \n\n, decoded up to eos \n\nCost. \nAutoregressive decoding needs M \nM \n\nsequential decoder passes to emit M \nM \n\ntokens (Vaswani et al., 2017 \n) \n. Diffusion decoding needs at most S \nS \n\npasses over the whole canvas in parallel, plus one encoder pass, and doubles the decoder passes only when guidance is on. The cost is set by S \nS \n\nand is independent of the transcript length M \nM \n\n. With S \n≈ \n8 \n≪ \nM \n\nS\\approx 8\\ll M \n\n, and the flat accuracy curve of Table 4 \n\n, this is the source of the speedup. \n\n4 \nExperimental Setup \nData. \nStage one, we train the English model on the 100 hour clean subset of LibriSpeech (Panayotov et al., 2015 \n) \n. The multilingual model warm-starts from the English checkpoint and continues on FLEURS (Conneau et al., 2023 \n) \nacross six languages, English, German, French, Spanish, Hindi, and Mandarin. A further stage adds VoxPopuli parliamentary speech (Wang et al., 2021 \n) \n. The model has seen roughly 219 hours of audio in total. \n\nOptimization. \nWe use AdamW with a learning rate of 1 \n​ \ne \n\n− \n3 \n\n1\\mathrm{e}{-3} \n\n, betas of 0.9 and 0.95, and weight decay of 0.01, with 100 warmup steps and a cosine decay to one tenth of the peak. We clip gradients at norm 1.0. The backbone runs in bfloat16 and the projector in float32 for stable updates. Batches hold 4 utterances with 2 gradient accumulation steps, reduced to 2 and 6 on the longer VoxPopuli material. All runs use a single H100. \n\nEvaluation. \nWe report word error rate with the Whisper text normalizer applied to both reference and hypothesis, which is the Open-ASR and Artificial Analysis convention. For Hindi and Mandarin we report character error rate, because word error rate penalizes scripts whose word boundaries do not match the reference segmentation and overstates the error. We also report throughput as a multiple of real time. \n\nConfiguration. \nTable 1 \n\nlists the settings used for the reported runs. \n\nSetting \nValue \n\nOptimizer \nAdamW ( \n0.9 \n, \n0.95 \n) \n\n(0.9,0.95) \n\n, weight decay 0.01 \n0.01 \n\nLearning rate \n1 \n​ \ne \n\n− \n3 \n\n1\\mathrm{e}{-3} \n\n, 100 warmup, cosine to 0.1 \n× \n\n0.1\\times \n\nGradient clip \n1.0 \n1.0 \n\nBatch × \n\\times \n\naccum \n4 \n× \n2 \n\n4\\times 2 \n\n(Libri/FLEURS), 2 \n× \n6 \n\n2\\times 6 \n\n(VoxPopuli) \n\nPrecision \nbf16 backbone, fp32 projector \n\nCanvas L \nL \n\n256 train, 192 inference \n\nSubsample / tokens \n8 \n× \n\n8\\times \n\n/ T \n= \n188 \n\nT{=}188 \n\nLoRA \nr \n= \n16 \n\nr{=}16 \n\n, α \n= \n32 \n\n\\alpha{=}32 \n\n, dropout 0.05 \n0.05 \n\n, enc+dec attn \n\nLoss weights \nλ \nar \n\n= \n1 \n\n\\lambda_{\\text{ar}}{=}1 \n\n, λ \nctc \n\n= \n1 \n\n\\lambda_{\\text{ctc}}{=}1 \n\n, w \n​ \n( \nγ \n) \n\n= \n1 \n\nw(\\gamma){=}1 \n\nInference \n8 steps, η \n= \n0.1 \n\n\\eta{=}0.1 \n\n, guidance w \n= \n1 \n\nw{=}1 \n\n, temp 0.8 \n→ \n0.4 \n\n0.8\\!\\to\\!0.4 \n\nTable 1: \nTraining and inference configuration for the reported runs. \n\n5 \nResults \n5.1 \nEnglish recognition and grounding dynamics \nOn LibriSpeech test-clean, English word error rate walked down over ten epochs, from roughly 90 percent early in training to about 50 percent, then to 14.6 percent, and finally to 6.6 percent at the last checkpoint ( n \n= \n100 \n\nn{=}100 \n\ntest-clean utterances). The two intermediate points come from small held-out samples and are approximate; the final number is on the full evaluation set. This is single-digit word error rate from a frozen 26B backbone, a frozen Whisper encoder, and about 42M trainable parameters. \n\nGrounding was not monotone in the metrics. Token accuracy reached 0.50 and CTC loss kept falling while the model still said nothing useful. A manual decode at 0.4 epochs showed the greedy CTC output emitting the unigram prior, the most frequent tokens in frequency order such as “the of to he”, with no relation to the audio, even though the loss curve looked healthy. Only repeated exposure over many passes brought the projector and the attention into a configuration that actually transcribes, so we ran a manual decode every half epoch. As training progressed the outputs moved from repeated fragments to fluent text with occasional acoustic slips, such as “tents” for “tense”, the error profile of a model transcribing from the audio rather than falling back on its text prior. \n\nTable 2 \n\nshows the same run in numbers. The autoregressive loss stays near chance and token accuracy hovers around 0.4 to 0.5 through the first epoch, then both move sharply once the projector grounds. Without the CTC term the same configuration did not ground within the compute we ran, which is the failure Section 3.6 \n\nanalyzes; we observed this during development rather than as a controlled ablation. \n\nStep \nVal AR loss \nVal token acc \n\n25 \n5.01 \n0.42 \n\n300 \n4.62 \n0.44 \n\n900 \n4.45 \n0.50 \n\n2808 (ep. 2) \n0.34 \n0.85 \n\nTable 2: \nGrounding dynamics on a held-out set of about 32 utterances. The autoregressive loss stays near chance and token accuracy plateaus while the model is ungrounded, then both improve sharply. Over the same span the CTC loss falls from 24 to 8.6 and then below 0.1. \n\n5.2 \nMultilingual recognition \nWarm-starting from English and training on FLEURS gave one adapter covering all six languages. We report the three for which we ran held-out evaluation, English, Hindi, and Mandarin. German, French, and Spanish are in the training mix but were not separately evaluated here. Adding VoxPopuli traded a small amount of read-speech accuracy for a gain on conversational and accented audio, a movement along the accuracy frontier rather than a free improvement. Table 3 \n\nreports the adapter under the Whisper normalizer. \n\nBenchmark \nMetric \nScore \nn \nn \n\nFLEURS English \nWER \n15.7% \n150 \n\nVoxPopuli English \nWER \n18.5% \n1000 \n\nFLEURS Hindi \nCER \n15.8% \n300 \n\nFLEURS Mandarin \nCER \n29.6% \n300 \n\nTable 3: \nMultilingual adapter, Whisper-normalized, with evaluation set sizes n \nn \n\n. Mandarin word error rate reads 40 percent under word segmentation, while the character error rate on the same transcripts is 29.6 percent. \n\n5.3 \nParallel decoding \nBecause the decoder refines the entire canvas at once, transcription cost is set by the number of denoising steps and not by the length of the transcript. Table 4 \n\nsweeps the step count on FLEURS English. The curve is close to flat. Moving from 8 steps to 48 buys about half a point of word error rate and costs roughly three times the latency. The model converges in about eight parallel passes. For a ten second clip this is on the order of one second of model time, and it does not grow with how much the speaker says. \n\nSteps \nFLEURS-en WER \nSpeed \n\n8 \n15.7% \n14.9 × \n\\times \n\n16 \n15.6% \n10.3 × \n\\times \n\n32 \n15.2% \n6.5 × \n\\times \n\n48 \n15.6% \n4.7 × \n\\times \n\nTable 4: \nWord error rate and throughput as a multiple of real time against the number of denoising steps (FLEURS English, n \n= \n150 \n\nn{=}150 \n\n). \n\n5.4 \nComparison with diffusion and autoregressive systems \nTable 5 \n\nplaces our LibriSpeech test-clean result beside other diffusion and non-autoregressive systems. These are the numbers reported in the respective papers, not controlled reruns, and the systems differ in encoder, training data, tokenization, and decoding, so the table is context rather than a head-to-head comparison. We place our result next to TransFusion (Baas et al., 2022 \n) \nand Whisfusion (Kwon et al., 2025 \n) \nfor reference, not to claim a controlled win. \n\nModel \nApproach \nWER \n\nTransFusion \nmultinomial diffusion \n∼ \n\\sim \n\n6–7% \n\nWhisfusion \nmasked diffusion \n8.3% \n\nOurs \nfrozen diffusion LM \n6.6% \n\nTable 5: \nDiffusion and non-autoregressive speech recognition on LibriSpeech test-clean. Baseline numbers are as reported by their authors under differing encoders, data, and decoding, and are not controlled reruns; only our row ( n \n= \n100 \n\nn{=}100 \n\n) is measured in this work. TransFusion is a character-level proof of concept. \n\nAgainst autoregressive Whisper, which remains the strongest baseline, our model trails, as Table 6 \n\nshows. All numbers use the Whisper normalizer. The gap is largest on FLEURS and VoxPopuli and smallest on LibriSpeech, the one domain where we had a hundred clean hours. \n\nBenchmark \nOurs \nW-small \nW-large-v3 \n\nLibriSpeech clean \n6.6% \n∼ \n\\sim \n\n3.4% \n∼ \n\\sim \n\n2.0% \n\nFLEURS-en \n15.7% \n∼ \n\\sim \n\n9–10% \n∼ \n\\sim \n\n4–5% \n\nVoxPopuli-en \n18.5% \n∼ \n\\sim \n\n9–11% \n∼ \n\\sim \n\n7–10% \n\nTable 6: \nContext against autoregressive Whisper. The Whisper columns are published ranges, not controlled reruns; only the Ours column is measured here (LibriSpeech n \n= \n100 \n\nn{=}100 \n\n, FLEURS-en n \n= \n150 \n\nn{=}150 \n\n, VoxPopuli-en n \n= \n1000 \n\nn{=}1000 \n\n). \n\n5.5 \nWhat is the bottleneck \nWe ran ablations to locate the source of the residual error, because the answer decides whether the method is broken or simply undertrained. We ruled out one suspect at a time. \n\nFirst, encoder quality. We swapped the Whisper-small front end for Whisper-large-v3 and retrained on the same 100 hour set. Word error rate at matched data moved from 14.75 percent at three epochs to 13.15 at six and 8.95 at eight, which is roughly even with the small-encoder run at the same data scale. A stronger encoder did not move the floor at this data budget, so the encoder is not the current limit. \n\nSecond, audio resolution. We reduced the subsample factor below eight to give the projector more audio tokens per second. This regressed to 44.7 percent word error rate rather than improving, so token resolution is not the limit either, and the eight-fold subsample is not starving the decoder. \n\nThird, decode steps. The step sweep in Table 4 \n\nis flat, so the sampler is not leaving accuracy on the table. \n\nWith encoder quality, resolution, and step count ruled out, the most likely remaining explanation is data scale and adapter alignment. Whisper-large-v3 was trained on a few million hours and Whisper-small on about 680 thousand. This model has seen roughly 219 hours, three orders of magnitude fewer, and it already reached 6.6 percent on the single domain where it had a hundred clean hours. The frontend ablation points the same way, since a stronger encoder did not help at this data budget, which is what one expects when the bottleneck is data rather than features. The evidence is consistent with a data bottleneck rather than a broken method, but we cannot establish this without a scaling curve, which we leave to future work. \n\n6 \nRelated Work \nHow speech recognition decodes. \nEnd-to-end recognition grew from two ideas. Connectionist temporal classification aligns a frame sequence to a shorter label sequence without explicit segmentation (Graves et al., 2006 \n) \n. Attention-based sequence-to-sequence models instead let a decoder attend over the encoded audio and spell the transcript (Chan et al., 2016 \n) \n, a pattern the transformer generalized (Vaswani et al., 2017 \n) \n. Most progress since then has come from stronger encoders, including self-supervised representations (Baevski et al., 2020 \n) \nand convolution-augmented transformers (Gulati et al., 2020 \n) \n, and from scale and weak supervision (Radford et al., 2023 \n) \n. In all of these the transcript is produced one token at a time. \n\nNon-autoregressive and diffusion text generation. \nParallel generation began with non-autoregressive translation, which emits the whole target at once (Gu et al., 2018 \n) \n. Diffusion models, developed for continuous data (Sohl-Dickstein et al., 2015 \n; Ho et al., 2020 \n) \n, were brought to language both by embedding tokens in a continuous space (Li et al., 2022 \n; Gong et al., 2023 \n) \nand by defining the corruption directly on discrete tokens (Austin et al., 2021 \n; Lou et al., 2024 \n) \n. Self-conditioning improved discrete diffusion by feeding the previous prediction back into the next step (Chen et al., 2023 \n) \n, a technique our sampler uses. Large masked-diffusion language models now reach quality competitive with autoregressive models of similar size (Nie et al., 2025 \n) \n. DiffusionGemma sits in this family but corrupts toward uniform random tokens rather than an absorbing mask. \n\nDiffusion speech recognition and audio language models. \nTwo systems put diffusion decoding directly on speech. TransFusion transcribed characters with multinomial diffusion as a proof of concept (Baas et al., 2022 \n) \n, and Whisfusion trained a masked-diffusion decoder over frozen Whisper features (Kwon et al., 2025 \n) \n. Both build that decoder from scratch, whereas we reuse one that already exists. Separately, a large body of work gives new modalities to frozen or lightly adapted language models through a trained connector, for vision (Liu et al., 2023 \n) \nand for audio (Chu et al., 2023 \n; Rubenstein et al., 2023 \n) \n, often on top of open model families such as Gemma (Gemma Team, 2024 \n) \n. Our work joins these two threads. We reuse an off-the-shelf diffusion language model with no new decoder, connect a frozen speech encoder through a projector and low-rank adapters (Hu et al., 2022 \n) \n, ground it with connectionist temporal classification (Graves et al., 2006 \n) \n, decode with uniform random-token diffusion rather than absorbing masks, and train one adapter on six languages. \n\n7 \nLimitations \nThe model trails autoregressive Whisper on every benchmark we tested, by the largest margin on multilingual read speech. The evidence points to data scale as the cause rather than architecture, but that remains a hypothesis until we train on substantially more audio. The Whisper encoder fixes the input window at thirty seconds, so real streaming is not possible and long audio is handled by silence segmentation, which can err when speech has no clear pauses. The diffusion decoder can produce repetition artifacts on short utterances, which we currently remove with a post-processing pass rather than at the source. Finally, our comparisons to Whisper use published ranges under the same normalizer rather than a single controlled re-run of every baseline, so the Whisper columns should be read as reference points rather than exact head-to-head numbers. \n\n8 \nConclusion \nA frozen language model can learn to hear if the audio projector is supervised directly rather than only through attention. Loss curves and token accuracy will look healthy well before the model is actually grounded, so manual decoding matters during training. Once grounded, diffusion decoding makes the length of what a speaker said stop mattering for cost, because recognition converges in about eight parallel steps. The grounding recipe, the CTC unlock, and the diffusion decoder all work today; what the model still lacks is exposure to more hours of audio. \n\nReferences \nAustin et al. (2021) \nJacob Austin, Daniel D. Johnson, Jonathan Ho, Daniel Tarlow, and Rianne van den Berg. 2021. \nStructured denoising diffusion models in discrete state-spaces. \nIn Advances in Neural Information Processing Systems \n. arXiv:2107.03006. \n\nBaas et al. (2022) \nMatthew Baas, Kevin Eloff, and Herman Kamper. 2022. \nTransFusion: Transcribing speech with multinomial diffusion \n. \nIn Southern African Conference for Artificial Intelligence Research (SACAIR) \n. arXiv:2210.07677. \n\nBaevski et al. (2020) \nAlexei Baevski, Henry Zhou, Abdelrahman Mohamed, and Michael Auli. 2020. \nwav2vec 2.0: A framework for self-supervised learning of speech representations. \nIn Advances in Neural Information Processing Systems \n. arXiv:2006.11477. \n\nChan et al. (2016) \nWilliam Chan, Navdeep Jaitly, Quoc V. Le, and Oriol Vinyals. 2016. \nListen, attend and spell: A neural network for large vocabulary conversational speech recognition. \nIn IEEE International Conference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal Processing (ICASSP) \n. arXiv:1508.01211. \n\nChen et al. (2023) \nTing Ch